data.title: Business teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in business administration and management, such as accounting, finance, human resources, labor and industrial relations, marketing, and operations research. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Math and computer science teachers, postsecondary
data.soc_title: Math and Computer Science Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Computer science teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in computer science. May specialize in a field of computer science, such as the design and function of computers or operations and research analysis. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Mathematical science teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses pertaining to mathematical concepts, statistics, and actuarial science and to the application of original and standardized mathematical techniques in solving specific problems and situations. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Engineering and architecture teachers, postsecondary
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Architecture teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in architecture and architectural design, such as architectural environmental design, interior architecture/design, and landscape architecture. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Engineering teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses pertaining to the application of physical laws and principles of engineering for the development of machines, materials, instruments, processes, and services. Includes teachers of subjects such as chemical, civil, electrical, industrial, mechanical, mineral, and petroleum engineering. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research. Excludes “Computer Science Teachers, Postsecondary” (25-1021).

data.title: Life sciences teachers, postsecondary
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Agricultural sciences teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in the agricultural sciences. Includes teachers of agronomy, dairy sciences, fisheries management, horticultural sciences, poultry sciences, range management, and agricultural soil conservation. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research. Excludes “Forestry and Conservation Science Teachers, Postsecondary” (25-1043).

data.title: Biological science teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in biological sciences. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Forestry and conservation science teachers, postsecondary
data.soc_title: Forestry and Conservation Science Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in forestry and conservation science. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research. Excludes “Agricultural Science Teachers, Postsecondary” (25-1041) and “Environmental Science Teachers, Postsecondary” (25-1053).

data.title: Physical sciences teachers, postsecondary
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Atmospheric, earth, etc
data.soc_title: Atmospheric, Earth, Marine, and Space Sciences Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in the physical sciences, except chemistry and physics. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching, and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Chemistry teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses pertaining to the chemical and physical properties and compositional changes of substances. Work may include providing instruction in the methods of qualitative and quantitative chemical analysis. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching, and those who do a combination of teaching and research. Excludes “Biological Science Teachers, Postsecondary” (25-1042) who teach biochemistry.

data.title: Environmental science teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in environmental science. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research. Excludes “Forestry and Conservation Science Teachers, Postsecondary” (25-1043).

data.title: Physics teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses pertaining to the laws of matter and energy. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Social sciences teachers, postsecondary
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Anthropology and archeology teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in anthropology or archeology. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Area, ethnic, etc
data.soc_title: Area, Ethnic, and Cultural Studies Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses pertaining to the culture and development of an area, an ethnic group, or any other group, such as Latin American studies, women’s studies, or urban affairs. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Economics teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in economics. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Geography teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in geography. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Political science teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in political science, international affairs, and international relations. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Psychology teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in psychology, such as child, clinical, and developmental psychology, and psychological counseling. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Sociology teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in sociology. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Social sciences teachers, postsecondary, etc
data.soc_title: Social Sciences Teachers, Postsecondary, All Other
data.def: All postsecondary social sciences teachers not listed separately.

data.title: Health teachers, postsecondary
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Health specialties teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in health specialties, in fields such as dentistry, laboratory technology, medicine, pharmacy, public health, therapy, and veterinary medicine. Excludes “Biological Science Teachers, Postsecondary” (25-1042) and “Nursing Instructors and Teachers, Postsecondary” (25-1072) who teach medical science.

data.title: Nursing instructors and teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Demonstrate and teach patient care in classroom and clinical units to nursing students. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Education and library science teachers, postsecondary
data.soc_title: Education and Library Science Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Education teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses pertaining to education, such as counseling, curriculum, guidance, instruction, teacher education, and teaching English as a second language. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Library science teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in library science. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Law, criminal justice, etc
data.soc_title: Law, Criminal Justice, and Social Work Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Criminal justice and law enforcement teachers, postsecondary
data.soc_title: Criminal Justice and Law Enforcement Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in criminal justice, corrections, and law enforcement administration. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Law teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in law. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Social work teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in social work. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Arts, communications, etc
data.soc_title: Arts, Communications, History, and Humanities Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Art, drama, etc
data.soc_title: Art, Drama, and Music Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in drama, music, and the arts including fine and applied art, such as painting and sculpture, or design and crafts. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Communications teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in communications, such as organizational communications, public relations, radio/television broadcasting, and journalism. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: English language and literature teachers, postsecondary
data.soc_title: English Language and Literature Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in English language and literature, including linguistics and comparative literature. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Foreign language and literature teachers, postsecondary
data.soc_title: Foreign Language and Literature Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: Teach languages and literature courses in languages other than English. Includes teachers of American Sign Language (ASL). Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: History teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in human history and historiography. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Philosophy and religion teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in philosophy, religion, and theology. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Miscellaneous postsecondary teachers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Family and consumer sciences teachers, postsecondary
data.soc_title: Family and Consumer Sciences Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses in childcare, family relations, finance, nutrition, and related subjects pertaining to home management. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Recreation and fitness studies teachers, postsecondary
data.soc_title: Recreation and Fitness Studies Teachers, Postsecondary
data.def: Teach courses pertaining to recreation, leisure, and fitness studies, including exercise physiology and facilities management. Includes both teachers primarily engaged in teaching and those who do a combination of teaching and research.

data.title: Career/technical education teachers, postsecondary
data.def: Teach vocational courses intended to provide occupational training below the baccalaureate level in subjects such as construction, mechanics/repair, manufacturing, transportation, or cosmetology, primarily to students who have graduated from or left high school. Teaching takes place in public or private schools whose primary business is academic or vocational education. Excludes “Training and Development Specialists” (13-1151), “Adult Basic Education, Adult Secondary Education, and English as a Second Language Instructors” (25-3011), and postsecondary teachers classified elsewhere in the 25-1000 minor group. Flight instructors are included with “Aircraft Pilots and Flight Engineers” (53-2010).

data.title: Postsecondary teachers, all other
data.def: All postsecondary teachers not listed separately.

data.title: Preschool, elementary, etc
data.soc_title: Preschool, Elementary, Middle, Secondary, and Special Education Teachers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Preschool and kindergarten teachers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Preschool teachers, except special education
data.def: Instruct preschool-aged students, following curricula or lesson plans, in activities designed to promote social, physical, and intellectual growth. Excludes “Special Education Teachers” (25-2050), “Substitute Teachers, Short-Term” (25-3031), and “Childcare Workers” (39-9011).

data.title: Kindergarten teachers, except special education
data.def: Teach academic and social skills to kindergarten students. Excludes “Special Education Teachers” (25-2050) and “Substitute Teachers, Short-Term” (25-3031).

data.title: Elementary and middle school teachers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Elementary school teachers, except special education
data.soc_title: Elementary School Teachers, Except Special Education
data.def: Teach academic and social skills to students at the elementary school level. Excludes “Special Education Teachers” (25-2050) and “Substitute Teachers, Short-Term” (25-3031).

data.title: Middle school teachers, except special and career/technical education
data.soc_title: Middle School Teachers, Except Special and Career/Technical Education
data.def: Teach one or more subjects to students at the middle, intermediate, or junior high school level. Excludes “Career/Technical Education Teachers, Middle School” (25-2023), “Special Education Teachers” (25-2050), and “Substitute Teachers, Short Term” (25-3031).

data.title: Career/technical education teachers, middle school
data.def: Teach occupational, vocational, career, or technical subjects to students at the middle, intermediate, or junior high school level. Excludes “Special Education Teachers” (25-2050) and “Substitute Teachers, Short-Term” (25-3031).

data.title: Secondary school teachers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Secondary school teachers, except special and career/technical education
data.soc_title: Secondary School Teachers, Except Special and Career/Technical Education
data.def: Teach one or more subjects to students at the secondary school level. Excludes “Career/Technical Education Teachers, Secondary School” (25-2032), “Special Education Teachers” (25-2050), and “Substitute Teachers, Short-Term” (25-3031).

data.title: Career/technical education teachers, secondary school
data.def: Teach occupational, vocational, career, or technical subjects to students at the secondary school level. Excludes “Special Education Teachers” (25-2050), and “Substitute Teachers, Short-Term” (25-3031).

data.title: Special education teachers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Special education teachers, preschool
data.def: Teach academic, social, and life skills to preschool-aged students with learning, emotional, or physical disabilities. Includes teachers who specialize and work with students who are blind or have visual impairments; students who are deaf or have hearing impairments; and students with intellectual disabilities. Excludes “Substitute Teachers, Short-Term” (25-3031).

data.title: Special education teachers, kindergarten and elementary school
data.def: No job definition found.

data.title: Special education teachers, middle school
data.def: Teach academic, social, and life skills to middle school students with learning, emotional, or physical disabilities. Includes teachers who specialize and work with students who are blind or have visual impairments; students who are deaf or have hearing impairments; and students with intellectual disabilities. Excludes “Substitute Teachers, Short-Term” (25-3031).

data.title: Special education teachers, secondary school
data.def: Teach academic, social, and life skills to secondary school students with learning, emotional, or physical disabilities. Includes teachers who specialize and work with students who are blind or have visual impairments; students who are deaf or have hearing impairments; and students with intellectual disabilities. Excludes “Substitute Teachers, Short-Term” (25-3031).

data.title: Special education teachers, all other
data.def: All special education teachers not listed separately.

data.title: Other teachers and instructors
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Adult basic education, adult secondary education, etc
data.soc_title: Adult Basic Education, Adult Secondary Education, and English as a Second Language Instructors
data.def: Teach or instruct out-of-school youths and adults in basic education, literacy, or English as a Second Language classes, or in classes for earning a high school equivalency credential.

data.title: Self-enrichment teachers
data.def: Teach or instruct individuals or groups for the primary purpose of self-enrichment or recreation, rather than for an occupational objective, educational attainment, competition, or fitness. Excludes “Coaches and Scouts” (27-2022) and “Exercise Trainers and Group Fitness Instructors” (39-9031). Flight instructors are included with “Aircraft Pilots and Flight Engineers” (53-2010).

data.title: Substitute teachers, short-term
data.def: Teach students on a short-term basis as a temporary replacement for a regular classroom teacher, typically using the regular teacher’s lesson plan. Excludes long-term substitute teachers who perform all the duties of a regular teacher; these teachers are coded within the 25-1000 or 25-2000 minor groups.

data.title: Tutors
data.def: Instruct individual students or small groups of students in academic subjects to support formal class instruction or to prepare students for standardized or admissions tests. Excludes “Postsecondary Teachers” (25-1000), “Elementary, Middle, Secondary, and Special Education Teachers” (25-2000), “Adult Basic Education, Adult Secondary Education, and English as a Second Language Instructors” (25-3011), and “Self-Enrichment Teachers” (25-3021).

data.title: Teachers and instructors, all other
data.def: All teachers and instructors not listed separately.

data.title: Librarians, curators, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Archivists, curators, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Archivists
data.def: Appraise, edit, and direct safekeeping of permanent records and historically valuable documents. Participate in research activities based on archival materials.

data.title: Curators
data.def: Administer collections, such as artwork, collectibles, historic items, or scientific specimens of museums or other institutions. May conduct instructional, research, or public service activities of institution.

data.title: Museum technicians and conservators
data.def: Restore, maintain, or prepare objects in museum collections for storage, research, or exhibit. May work with specimens such as fossils, skeletal parts, or botanicals; or artifacts, textiles, or art. May identify and record objects or install and arrange them in exhibits. Includes book or document conservators.

data.title: Librarians and media collections specialists
data.def: Administer and maintain libraries or collections of information, for public or private access through reference or borrowing. Work in a variety of settings, such as educational institutions, museums, and corporations, and with various types of informational materials, such as books, periodicals, recordings, films, and databases. Tasks may include acquiring, cataloging, and circulating library materials, and user services such as locating and organizing information, providing instruction on how to access information, and setting up and operating a library’s media equipment.

data.title: Library technicians
data.def: Assist librarians by helping readers in the use of library catalogs, databases, and indexes to locate books and other materials; and by answering questions that require only brief consultation of standard reference. Compile records; sort and shelve books or other media; remove or repair damaged books or other media; register patrons; and check materials in and out of the circulation process. Replace materials in shelving area (stacks) or files. Includes bookmobile drivers who assist with providing services in mobile libraries.

data.title: Other educational instruction and library jobs
data.soc_title: Other Educational Instruction and Library Occupations
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Farm and home management educators
data.def: Instruct and advise individuals and families engaged in agriculture, agricultural-related processes, or home management activities. Demonstrate procedures and apply research findings to advance agricultural and home management activities. May develop educational outreach programs. May instruct on either agricultural issues such as agricultural processes and techniques, pest management, and food safety, or on home management issues such as budgeting, nutrition, and child development. Excludes “Dietitians and Nutritionists” (29-1031).

data.title: Instructional coordinators
data.def: Develop instructional material, coordinate educational content, and incorporate current technology into instruction in order to provide guidelines to educators and instructors for developing curricula and conducting courses. May train and coach teachers. Includes educational consultants and specialists, and instructional material directors.

data.title: Teaching assistants
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Teaching assistants, postsecondary
data.def: Assist faculty or other instructional staff in postsecondary institutions by performing instructional support activities, such as developing teaching materials, leading discussion groups, preparing and giving examinations, and grading examinations or papers. Graduate students who teach one or more full courses should be classified in the 25-1000 minor group.

data.title: Teaching assistants, except postsecondary
data.def: No job definition found.

data.title: Educational instruction and library workers, all other
data.soc_title: Educational Instruction and Library Workers, All Other
data.def: All educational instruction and library workers not listed separately.

data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Art and design workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Artists and related workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Art directors
data.def: Formulate design concepts and presentation approaches for visual productions and media, such as print, broadcasting, video, and film. Direct workers engaged in artwork or layout design. Excludes “Set and Exhibit Designers” (27-1027).

data.title: Craft artists
data.def: Create or reproduce handmade objects for sale and exhibition using a variety of techniques, such as welding, weaving, pottery, and needlecraft.

data.title: Fine artists, including painters, etc
data.soc_title: Fine Artists, Including Painters, Sculptors, and Illustrators
data.def: Create original artwork using any of a wide variety of media and techniques.

data.title: Special effects artists and animators
data.def: Create special effects or animations using film, video, computers, or other electronic tools and media for use in products, such as computer games, movies, music videos, and commercials.

data.title: Artists and related workers, all other
data.soc_title: Artists and Related Workers, All Other
data.def: All artists and related workers not listed separately.

data.title: Designers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Commercial and industrial designers
data.def: Design and develop manufactured products, such as cars, home appliances, and children’s toys. Combine artistic talent with research on product use, marketing, and materials to create the most functional and appealing product design.

data.title: Fashion designers
data.def: Design clothing and accessories. Create original designs or adapt fashion trends.

data.title: Floral designers
data.def: Design, cut, and arrange live, dried, or artificial flowers and foliage.

data.title: Graphic designers
data.def: Design or create graphics to meet specific commercial or promotional needs, such as packaging, displays, or logos. May use a variety of mediums to achieve artistic or decorative effects. Excludes “Web and Digital Interface Designers” (15-1255).

data.title: Interior designers
data.def: Plan, design, and furnish the internal space of rooms or buildings. Design interior environments or create physical layouts that are practical, aesthetic, and conducive to the intended purposes. May specialize in a particular field, style, or phase of interior design. Excludes “Merchandise Displayers and Window Trimmers” (27-1026).

data.title: Merchandise displayers and window trimmers
data.def: Plan and erect commercial displays, such as those in windows and interiors of retail stores and at trade exhibitions.

data.title: Set and exhibit designers
data.def: Design special exhibits and sets for film, video, television, and theater productions. May study scripts, confer with directors, and conduct research to determine appropriate architectural styles.

data.title: Designers, all other
data.def: All designers not listed separately.

data.title: Entertainers and performers, sports and related workers
data.soc_title: Entertainers and Performers, Sports and Related Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Actors, producers, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Actors
data.def: Play parts in stage, television, radio, video, or film productions, or other settings for entertainment, information, or instruction. Interpret serious or comic role by speech, gesture, and body movement to entertain or inform audience. May dance and sing.

data.title: Producers and directors
data.def: Produce or direct stage, television, radio, video, or film productions for entertainment, information, or instruction. Responsible for creative decisions, such as interpretation of script, choice of actors or guests, set design, sound, special effects, and choreography.

data.title: Athletes, coaches, etc
data.soc_title: Athletes, Coaches, Umpires, and Related Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Athletes and sports competitors
data.def: Compete in athletic events.

data.title: Coaches and scouts
data.def: Instruct or coach groups or individuals in the fundamentals of sports for the primary purpose of competition. Demonstrate techniques and methods of participation. May evaluate athletes’ strengths and weaknesses as possible recruits or to improve the athletes’ technique to prepare them for competition. Those required to hold teaching certifications should be reported in the appropriate teaching category. Excludes “Athletic Trainers” (29-9091).

data.title: Umpires, referees, etc
data.soc_title: Umpires, Referees, and Other Sports Officials
data.def: Officiate at competitive athletic or sporting events. Detect infractions of rules and decide penalties according to established regulations. Includes all sporting officials, referees, and competition judges.

data.title: Dancers and choreographers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Dancers
data.def: Perform dances. May perform on stage, for broadcasting, or for video recording.

data.title: Choreographers
data.def: Create new dance routines. Rehearse performance of routines. May direct and stage presentations.

data.title: Musicians, singers, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Music directors and composers
data.def: Conduct, direct, plan, and lead instrumental or vocal performances by musical artists or groups, such as orchestras, bands, choirs, and glee clubs; or create original works of music.

data.title: Musicians and singers
data.def: Play one or more musical instruments or sing. May perform on stage, for broadcasting, or for sound or video recording.

data.title: Miscellaneous entertainers and performers, sports and related workers
data.soc_title: Miscellaneous Entertainers and Performers, Sports and Related Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Disc jockeys, except radio
data.def: Play prerecorded music for live audiences at venues or events such as clubs, parties, or wedding receptions. May use techniques such as mixing, cutting, or sampling to manipulate recordings. May also perform as emcee (master of ceremonies). Radio disc jockeys are included in “Broadcast Announcers and Radio Disc Jockeys” (27-3011). Excludes “Musicians and Singers” (27-2042), “Audio and Video Technicians” (27-4011), and “Sound Engineering Technicians” (27-4014).

data.title: Entertainers and performers, sports and related workers, etc
data.soc_title: Entertainers and Performers, Sports and Related Workers, All Other
data.def: All entertainers and performers, sports and related workers not listed separately.

data.title: Media and communication workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Broadcast announcers and radio disc jockeys
data.soc_title: Broadcast Announcers and Radio Disc Jockeys
data.def: Speak or read from scripted materials, such as news reports or commercial messages, on radio, television, or other communications media. May play and queue music, announce artist or title of performance, identify station, or interview guests. Excludes “News Analysts, Reporters, and Journalists” (27-3023).

data.title: News analysts, reporters, etc
data.def: Narrate or write news stories, reviews, or commentary for print, broadcast, or other communications media such as newspapers, magazines, radio, or television. May collect and analyze information through interview, investigation, or observation.

data.title: Public relations specialists
data.def: Promote or create an intended public image for individuals, groups, or organizations. May write or select material for release to various communications media. May specialize in using social media.

data.title: Writers and editors
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Editors
data.def: Plan, coordinate, revise, or edit written material. May review proposals and drafts for possible publication.

data.title: Technical writers
data.def: Write technical materials, such as equipment manuals, appendices, or operating and maintenance instructions. May assist in layout work.

data.title: Writers and authors
data.def: Originate and prepare written material, such as scripts, stories, advertisements, and other material. Excludes “News Analysts, Reporters, and Journalists” (27-3023), “Public Relations Specialists” (27-3031), and “Technical Writers” (27-3042).

data.title: Miscellaneous media and communication workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Interpreters and translators
data.def: Interpret oral or sign language, or translate written text from one language into another.

data.title: Court reporters and simultaneous captioners
data.def: Use verbatim methods and equipment to capture, store, retrieve, and transcribe pretrial and trial proceedings or other information. Includes stenocaptioners who operate computerized stenographic captioning equipment to provide captions of live or prerecorded broadcasts for hearing-impaired viewers.

data.title: Media and communication workers, all other
data.soc_title: Media and Communication Workers, All Other
data.def: All media and communication workers not listed separately.

data.title: Media and communication equipment workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Broadcast, sound, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Audio and video technicians
data.def: Set up, maintain, and dismantle audio and video equipment, such as microphones, sound speakers, connecting wires and cables, sound and mixing boards, video cameras, video monitors and servers, and related electronic equipment for live or recorded events, such as concerts, meetings, conventions, presentations, podcasts, news conferences, and sporting events. Excludes “Sound Engineering Technicians” (27-4014), “Lighting Technicians” (27-4015), and “Audiovisual Equipment Installers and Repairers” (49-2097).

data.title: Broadcast technicians
data.def: Set up, operate, and maintain the electronic equipment used to acquire, edit, and transmit audio and video for radio or television programs. Control and adjust incoming and outgoing broadcast signals to regulate sound volume, signal strength, and signal clarity. Operate satellite, microwave, or other transmitter equipment to broadcast radio or television programs.

data.title: Sound engineering technicians
data.def: Assemble and operate equipment to record, synchronize, mix, edit, or reproduce sound, including music, voices, or sound effects, for theater, video, film, television, podcasts, sporting events, and other productions. Excludes “Audio and Video Technicians” (27-4011).

data.title: Lighting technicians
data.def: Set up, maintain, and dismantle light fixtures, lighting control devices, and the associated lighting electrical and rigging equipment used for photography, television, film, video, and live productions. May focus or operate light fixtures, or attach color filters or other lighting accessories. Excludes “Audio and Video Technicians” (27-4011).

data.title: Photographers
data.def: Photograph people, landscapes, merchandise, or other subjects. May use lighting equipment to enhance a subject’s appearance. May use editing software to produce finished images and prints. Includes commercial and industrial photographers, scientific photographers, and photojournalists. Excludes “Camera Operators, Television, Video, and Film” (27-4031).

data.title: Television, video, etc
data.soc_title: Television, Video, and Film Camera Operators and Editors
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Camera operators, television, etc
data.soc_title: Camera Operators, Television, Video, and Film
data.def: Operate television, video, or film camera to record images or scenes for television, video, or film productions.

data.title: Film and video editors
data.def: Edit moving images on film, video, or other media. May work with a producer or director to organize images for final production. May edit or synchronize soundtracks with images. Excludes “Sound Engineering Technicians” (27-4014).

data.title: Media and communication equipment workers, all other
data.soc_title: Media and Communication Equipment Workers, All Other
data.def: All media and communication equipment workers not listed separately.

data.title: Healthcare practitioners and technical jobs
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Healthcare diagnosing or treating practitioners
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Chiropractors
data.def: Assess, treat, and care for patients by manipulation of spine and musculoskeletal system. May provide spinal adjustment or address sacral or pelvic misalignment.

data.title: Dentists
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Dentists, general
data.def: Examine, diagnose, and treat diseases, injuries, and malformations of teeth and gums. May treat diseases of nerve, pulp, and other dental tissues affecting oral hygiene and retention of teeth. May fit dental appliances or provide preventive care. Excludes “Oral and Maxillofacial Surgeons” (29-1022), “Orthodontists” (29-1023), “Prosthodontists” (29-1024), and “Dentists, All Other Specialists” (29-1029).

data.title: Oral and maxillofacial surgeons
data.def: Perform surgery and related procedures on the hard and soft tissues of the oral and maxillofacial regions to treat diseases, injuries, or defects. May diagnose problems of the oral and maxillofacial regions. May perform surgery to improve function or appearance.

data.title: Orthodontists
data.def: Examine, diagnose, and treat dental malocclusions and oral cavity anomalies. Design and fabricate appliances to realign teeth and jaws to produce and maintain normal function and to improve appearance.

data.title: Prosthodontists
data.def: Diagnose, treat, rehabilitate, design, and fit prostheses that maintain oral function, health, and appearance for patients with clinical conditions associated with teeth, oral and maxillofacial tissues, or the jaw.

data.title: Dentists, all other specialists
data.def: All dentists not listed separately.

data.title: Dietitians and nutritionists
data.def: Plan and conduct food service or nutritional programs to assist in the promotion of health and control of disease. May supervise activities of a department providing quantity food services, counsel individuals, or conduct nutritional research.

data.title: Optometrists
data.def: Diagnose, manage, and treat conditions and diseases of the human eye and visual system. Examine eyes and visual system, diagnose problems or impairments, prescribe corrective lenses, and provide treatment. May prescribe therapeutic drugs to treat specific eye conditions. Ophthalmologists are included in “Ophthalmologists, Except Pediatric” (29-1241).

data.title: Pharmacists
data.def: Dispense drugs prescribed by physicians and other health practitioners and provide information to patients about medications and their use. May advise physicians and other health practitioners on the selection, dosage, interactions, and side effects of medications.

data.title: Physician assistants
data.def: Provide healthcare services typically performed by a physician, under the supervision of a physician. Conduct complete physicals, provide treatment, and counsel patients. May, in some cases, prescribe medication. Must graduate from an accredited educational program for physician assistants. Excludes “Registered Nurses” (29-1141), “Nurse Anesthetists” (29-1151), “Nurse Midwives” (29-1161), “Nurse Practitioners” (29-1171), “Emergency Medical Technicians” (29-2042), “Paramedics” (29-2043), “Surgical Assistants” (29-9093), and “Medical Assistants” (31-9092).

data.title: Podiatrists
data.def: Diagnose and treat diseases and deformities of the human foot.

data.title: Therapists
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Occupational therapists
data.def: Assess, plan, and organize rehabilitative programs that help build or restore vocational, homemaking, and daily living skills, as well as general independence, to persons with disabilities or developmental delays. Use therapeutic techniques, adapt the individual’s environment, teach skills, and modify specific tasks that present barriers to the individual. Excludes “Rehabilitation Counselors” (21-1015).

data.title: Physical therapists
data.def: Assess, plan, organize, and participate in rehabilitative programs that improve mobility, relieve pain, increase strength, and improve or correct disabling conditions resulting from disease or injury.

data.title: Radiation therapists
data.def: Provide radiation therapy to patients as prescribed by a radiation oncologist according to established practices and standards. Duties may include reviewing prescription and diagnosis; acting as liaison with physician and supportive care personnel; preparing equipment, such as immobilization, treatment, and protection devices; and maintaining records, reports, and files. May assist in dosimetry procedures and tumor localization.

data.title: Recreational therapists
data.def: Plan, direct, or coordinate medically-approved recreation programs for patients in hospitals, nursing homes, or other institutions. Activities include sports, trips, dramatics, social activities, and crafts. May assess a patient condition and recommend appropriate recreational activity. Excludes “Recreation Workers” (39-9032).

data.title: Respiratory therapists
data.def: Assess, treat, and care for patients with breathing disorders. Assume primary responsibility for all respiratory care modalities, including the supervision of respiratory therapy technicians. Initiate and conduct therapeutic procedures; maintain patient records; and select, assemble, check, and operate equipment.

data.title: Speech-language pathologists
data.def: Assess and treat persons with speech, language, voice, and fluency disorders. May select alternative communication systems and teach their use. May perform research related to speech and language problems.

data.title: Exercise physiologists
data.def: Assess, plan, or implement fitness programs that include exercise or physical activities such as those designed to improve cardiorespiratory function, body composition, muscular strength, muscular endurance, or flexibility. Excludes “Physical Therapists” (29-1123), “Athletic Trainers” (29-9091), and “Exercise Trainers and Group Fitness Instructors” (39-9031).

data.title: Therapists, all other
data.def: All therapists not listed separately.

data.title: Veterinarians
data.def: Diagnose, treat, or research diseases and injuries of animals. Includes veterinarians who conduct research and development, inspect livestock, or care for pets and companion animals.

data.title: Registered nurses
data.def: Assess patient health problems and needs, develop and implement nursing care plans, and maintain medical records. Administer nursing care to ill, injured, convalescent, or disabled patients. May advise patients on health maintenance and disease prevention or provide case management. Licensing or registration required. Includes Clinical Nurse Specialists. Excludes “Nurse Anesthetists” (29-1151), “Nurse Midwives” (29-1161), and “Nurse Practitioners” (29-1171).

data.title: Nurse anesthetists
data.def: Administer anesthesia, monitor patient’s vital signs, and oversee patient recovery from anesthesia. May assist anesthesiologists, surgeons, other physicians, or dentists. Must be registered nurses who have specialized graduate education.

data.title: Nurse midwives
data.def: Diagnose and coordinate all aspects of the birthing process, either independently or as part of a healthcare team. May provide well-woman gynecological care. Must have specialized, graduate nursing education.

data.title: Nurse practitioners
data.def: Diagnose and treat acute, episodic, or chronic illness, independently or as part of a healthcare team. May focus on health promotion and disease prevention. May order, perform, or interpret diagnostic tests such as lab work and x rays. May prescribe medication. Must be registered nurses who have specialized graduate education.

data.title: Audiologists
data.def: Assess and treat persons with hearing and related disorders. May fit hearing aids and provide auditory training. May perform research related to hearing problems.

data.title: Physicians
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Anesthesiologists
data.def: Administer anesthetics and analgesics for pain management prior to, during, or after surgery.

data.title: Cardiologists
data.def: Diagnose, treat, manage, and prevent diseases or conditions of the cardiovascular system. May further subspecialize in interventional procedures (e.g., balloon angioplasty and stent placement), echocardiography, or electrophysiology.

data.title: Dermatologists
data.def: Diagnose and treat diseases relating to the skin, hair, and nails. May perform both medical and dermatological surgery functions.

data.title: Emergency medicine physicians
data.def: Make immediate medical decisions and act to prevent death or further disability. Provide immediate recognition, evaluation, care, stabilization, and disposition of patients. May direct emergency medical staff in an emergency department.

data.title: Family medicine physicians
data.def: Diagnose, treat, and provide preventive care to individuals and families across the lifespan. May refer patients to specialists when needed for further diagnosis or treatment. Excludes “General Internal Medicine Physicians” (29-1216) and “Pediatricians, General” (29-1221).

data.title: General internal medicine physicians
data.def: Diagnose and provide nonsurgical treatment for a wide range of diseases and injuries of internal organ systems. Provide care mainly for adults and adolescents, and are based primarily in an outpatient care setting. Excludes “Family Medicine Physicians” (29-1215) and “Pediatricians, General” (29-1221).

data.title: Neurologists
data.def: Diagnose, manage, and treat disorders and diseases of the brain, spinal cord, and peripheral nerves, with a primarily nonsurgical focus.

data.title: Obstetricians and gynecologists
data.def: Provide medical care related to pregnancy or childbirth. Diagnose, treat, and help prevent diseases of women, particularly those affecting the reproductive system. May also provide general care to women. May perform both medical and gynecological surgery functions.

data.title: Pediatricians, general
data.def: Diagnose, treat, and help prevent diseases and injuries in children. May refer patients to specialists for further diagnosis or treatment, as needed. Excludes “Family Medicine Physicians” (29-1215) and “General Internal Medicine Physicians” (29-1216).

data.title: Physicians, pathologists
data.def: Diagnose diseases and conduct lab tests using organs, body tissues, and fluids. Includes medical examiners.

data.title: Psychiatrists
data.def: Diagnose, treat, and help prevent mental disorders. Excludes “Clinical and Counseling Psychologists” (19-3033) and “School Psychologists” (19-3034).

data.title: Radiologists
data.def: Diagnose and treat diseases and injuries using medical imaging techniques, such as x rays, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), nuclear medicine, and ultrasounds. May perform minimally invasive medical procedures and tests.

data.title: Physicians, all other
data.def: All physicians not listed separately.

data.title: Surgeons
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Ophthalmologists, except pediatric
data.def: Diagnose and perform surgery to treat and help prevent disorders and diseases of the eye. May also provide vision services for treatment including glasses and contacts. Excludes “Optometrists” (29-1041) and “Pediatric Surgeons” (29-1243).

data.title: Orthopedic surgeons, except pediatric
data.def: Diagnose and perform surgery to treat and prevent rheumatic and other diseases in the musculoskeletal system. Excludes “Pediatric Surgeons” (29-1243).

data.title: Pediatric surgeons
data.def: Diagnose and perform surgery to treat fetal abnormalities and birth defects, diseases, and injuries in fetuses, premature and newborn infants, children, and adolescents. Includes all pediatric surgical specialties and subspecialties. Excludes “Oral and Maxillofacial Surgeons” (29-1022), “Ophthalmologists, Except Pediatric” (29-1241), and “Orthopedic Surgeons, Except Pediatric” (29-1242).

data.title: Surgeons, all other
data.def: All surgeons not listed separately. Excludes “Oral and Maxillofacial Surgeons” (29-1022).

data.title: Miscellaneous healthcare diagnosing or treating practitioners
data.soc_title: Miscellaneous Healthcare Diagnosing or Treating Practitioners
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Acupuncturists
data.def: Diagnose, treat, and prevent disorders by stimulating specific acupuncture points within the body using acupuncture needles. May also use cups, nutritional supplements, therapeutic massage, acupressure, and other alternative health therapies. Excludes “Chiropractors” (29-1011).

data.title: Dental hygienists
data.def: Administer oral hygiene care to patients. Assess patient oral hygiene problems or needs and maintain health records. Advise patients on oral health maintenance and disease prevention. May provide advanced care such as providing fluoride treatment or administering topical anesthesia.

data.title: Healthcare diagnosing or treating practitioners, all other
data.soc_title: Healthcare Diagnosing or Treating Practitioners, All Other
data.def: All healthcare diagnosing or treating practitioners not listed separately.

data.title: Health technologists and technicians
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Clinical laboratory technologists and technicians
data.def: No job definition found.

data.title: Diagnostic related technologists and technicians
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Cardiovascular technologists and technicians
data.def: Conduct tests on pulmonary or cardiovascular systems of patients for diagnostic, therapeutic, or research purposes. May conduct or assist in electrocardiograms, cardiac catheterizations, pulmonary functions, lung capacity, and similar tests.

data.title: Diagnostic medical sonographers
data.def: Produce ultrasonic recordings of internal organs for use by physicians. Includes vascular technologists. Excludes “Cardiovascular Technologists and Technicians” (29-2031).

data.title: Nuclear medicine technologists
data.def: Prepare, administer, and measure radioactive isotopes in therapeutic, diagnostic, and tracer studies using a variety of radioisotope equipment. Prepare stock solutions of radioactive materials and calculate doses to be administered by radiologists. Subject patients to radiation. Execute blood volume, red cell survival, and fat absorption studies following standard laboratory techniques.

data.title: Radiologic technologists and technicians
data.def: Take x-rays and CAT scans or administer nonradioactive materials into patient’s bloodstream for diagnostic or research purposes. Includes radiologic technologists and technicians who specialize in other scanning modalities. Excludes “Diagnostic Medical Sonographers” (29-2032) and “Magnetic Resonance Imaging Technologists” (29-2035).

data.title: Magnetic resonance imaging technologists
data.def: Operate Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) scanners. Monitor patient safety and comfort, and view images of area being scanned to ensure quality of pictures. May administer gadolinium contrast dosage intravenously. May interview patient, explain MRI procedures, and position patient on examining table. May enter into the computer data such as patient history, anatomical area to be scanned, orientation specified, and position of entry.

data.title: Medical dosimetrists
data.def: Generate radiation treatment plans, develop radiation dose calculations, communicate and supervise the treatment plan implementation, and consult with members of radiation oncology team.

data.title: Emergency medical technicians and paramedics
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Emergency medical technicians
data.def: Assess injuries and illnesses and administer basic emergency medical care. May transport injured or sick persons to medical facilities. Excludes “Paramedics” (29-2043), “Firefighters” (33-2011), and “Ambulance Drivers and Attendants, Except Emergency Medical Technicians” (53-3011).

data.title: Paramedics
data.def: Administer basic or advanced emergency medical care and assess injuries and illnesses. May administer medication intravenously, use equipment such as EKGs, or administer advanced life support to sick or injured individuals. Excludes “Emergency Medical Technicians” (29-2042) and “Ambulance Drivers and Attendants, Except Emergency Medical Technicians” (53-3011).

data.title: Health practitioner support technologists and technicians
data.soc_title: Health Practitioner Support Technologists and Technicians
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Dietetic technicians
data.def: Assist in the provision of food service and nutritional programs, under the supervision of a dietitian. May plan and produce meals based on established guidelines, teach principles of food and nutrition, or counsel individuals.

data.title: Pharmacy technicians
data.def: Prepare medications under the direction of a pharmacist. May measure, mix, count out, label, and record amounts and dosages of medications according to prescription orders.

data.title: Psychiatric technicians
data.def: Care for individuals with mental or emotional conditions or disabilities, following the instructions of physicians or other health practitioners. Monitor patients’ physical and emotional well-being and report to medical staff. May participate in rehabilitation and treatment programs, help with personal hygiene, and administer oral or injectable medications.

data.title: Surgical technologists
data.def: Assist in operations, under the supervision of surgeons, registered nurses, or other surgical personnel. May help set up operating room, prepare and transport patients for surgery, adjust lights and equipment, pass instruments and other supplies to surgeons and surgeons’ assistants, hold retractors, cut sutures, and help count sponges, needles, supplies, and instruments. Excludes “Surgical Assistants” (29-9093).

data.title: Veterinary technologists and technicians
data.def: Perform medical tests in a laboratory environment for use in the treatment and diagnosis of diseases in animals. Prepare vaccines and serums for prevention of diseases. Prepare tissue samples, take blood samples, and execute laboratory tests, such as urinalysis and blood counts. Clean and sterilize instruments and materials and maintain equipment and machines. May assist a veterinarian during surgery.

data.title: Ophthalmic medical technicians
data.def: Assist ophthalmologists by performing ophthalmic clinical functions. May administer eye exams, administer eye medications, and instruct the patient in care and use of corrective lenses.

data.title: Licensed practical and licensed vocational nurses
data.soc_title: Licensed Practical and Licensed Vocational Nurses
data.def: Care for ill, injured, or convalescing patients or persons with disabilities in hospitals, nursing homes, clinics, private homes, group homes, and similar institutions. May work under the supervision of a registered nurse. Licensing required.

data.title: Medical records specialists
data.def: Compile, process, and maintain medical records of hospital and clinic patients in a manner consistent with medical, administrative, ethical, legal, and regulatory requirements of the healthcare system. Classify medical and healthcare concepts, including diagnosis, procedures, medical services, and equipment, into the healthcare industry’s numerical coding system. Includes medical coders. Excludes “Health Information Technologists and Medical Registrars” (29-9021) and “File Clerks” (43-4071).

data.title: Opticians, dispensing
data.def: Design, measure, fit, and adapt lenses and frames for client according to written optical prescription or specification. Assist client with inserting, removing, and caring for contact lenses. Assist client with selecting frames. Measure customer for size of eyeglasses and coordinate frames with facial and eye measurements and optical prescription. Prepare work order for optical laboratory containing instructions for grinding and mounting lenses in frames. Verify exactness of finished lens spectacles. Adjust frame and lens position to fit client. May shape or reshape frames. Includes contact lens opticians.

data.title: Miscellaneous health technologists and technicians
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Orthotists and prosthetists
data.def: Design, measure, fit, and adapt orthopedic braces, appliances or prostheses, such as limbs or facial parts for patients with disabling conditions.

data.title: Hearing aid specialists
data.def: Select and fit hearing aids for customers. Administer and interpret tests of hearing. Assess hearing instrument efficacy. Take ear impressions and prepare, design, and modify ear molds. Excludes “Audiologists” (29-1181).

data.title: Health technologists and technicians, all other
data.soc_title: Health Technologists and Technicians, All Other
data.def: All health technologists and technicians not listed separately.

data.title: Other healthcare practitioners and technical jobs
data.soc_title: Other Healthcare Practitioners and Technical Occupations
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Health information technologists and medical registrars
data.soc_title: Health Information Technologists and Medical Registrars
data.def: Apply knowledge of healthcare and information systems to assist in the design, development, and continued modification and analysis of computerized healthcare systems. Abstract, collect, and analyze treatment and followup information of patients. May educate staff and assist in problem solving to promote the implementation of the healthcare information system. May design, develop, test, and implement databases with complete history, diagnosis, treatment, and health status to help monitor diseases. Excludes “Medical Records Specialists” (29‐2072).

data.title: Miscellaneous health practitioners and technical workers
data.soc_title: Miscellaneous Health Practitioners and Technical Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Athletic trainers
data.def: Evaluate and treat musculoskeletal injuries or illnesses. Provide preventive, therapeutic, emergency, and rehabilitative care. Excludes “Physical Therapists” (29-1123).

data.title: Genetic counselors
data.def: Assess individual or family risk for a variety of inherited conditions, such as genetic disorders and birth defects. Provide information to other healthcare providers or to individuals and families concerned with the risk of inherited conditions. Advise individuals and families to support informed decisionmaking and coping methods for those at risk. May help conduct research related to genetic conditions or genetic counseling.

data.title: Surgical assistants
data.def: Assist in operations, under the supervision of surgeons. May, in accordance with state laws, help surgeons to make incisions and close surgical sites, manipulate or remove tissues, implant surgical devices or drains, suction the surgical site, place catheters, clamp or cauterize vessels or tissue, and apply dressings to surgical site. Excludes “Registered Nurses” (29-1141) and “Surgical Technologists” (29-2055).

data.title: Healthcare practitioners and technical workers, all other
data.soc_title: Healthcare Practitioners and Technical Workers, All Other
data.def: All healthcare practitioners and technical workers not listed separately.

data.title: Healthcare support jobs
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Home health and personal care aides; and nursing assistants, orderlies, etc
data.soc_title: Home Health and Personal Care Aides; and Nursing Assistants, Orderlies, and Psychiatric Aides
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Home health and personal care aides
data.soc_title: Home Health and Personal Care Aides
data.def: No job definition found.

data.title: Nursing assistants, orderlies, etc
data.soc_title: Nursing Assistants, Orderlies, and Psychiatric Aides
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Nursing assistants
data.def: Provide or assist with basic care or support under the direction of onsite licensed nursing staff. Perform duties such as monitoring of health status, feeding, bathing, dressing, grooming, toileting, or ambulation of patients in a health or nursing facility. May include medication administration and other health-related tasks. Includes nursing care attendants, nursing aides, and nursing attendants. Excludes “Home Health Aides” (31-1121), “Personal Care Aides” (31-1122), “Orderlies” (31-1132), and “Psychiatric Aides” (31-1133).

data.title: Orderlies
data.def: Transport patients to areas such as operating rooms or x-ray rooms using wheelchairs, stretchers, or moveable beds. May maintain stocks of supplies or clean and transport equipment. Excludes “Nursing Assistants” (31-1131). Psychiatric orderlies are included in “Psychiatric Aides” (31-1133).

data.title: Psychiatric aides
data.def: Assist mentally impaired or emotionally disturbed patients, working under direction of nursing and medical staff. May assist with daily living activities, lead patients in educational and recreational activities, or accompany patients to and from examinations and treatments. May restrain violent patients. Includes psychiatric orderlies.

data.title: Occupational therapy and physical therapist assistants and aides
data.soc_title: Occupational Therapy and Physical Therapist Assistants and Aides
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Occupational therapy assistants and aides
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Occupational therapy assistants
data.def: Assist occupational therapists in providing occupational therapy treatments and procedures. May, in accordance with state laws, assist in development of treatment plans, carry out routine functions, direct activity programs, and document the progress of treatments. Generally requires formal training.

data.title: Occupational therapy aides
data.def: Under close supervision of an occupational therapist or occupational therapy assistant, perform only delegated, selected, or routine tasks in specific situations. These duties include preparing patient and treatment room.

data.title: Physical therapist assistants and aides
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Physical therapist assistants
data.def: Assist physical therapists in providing physical therapy treatments and procedures. May, in accordance with state laws, assist in the development of treatment plans, carry out routine functions, document the progress of treatment, and modify specific treatments in accordance with patient status and within the scope of treatment plans established by a physical therapist. Generally requires formal training.

data.title: Physical therapist aides
data.def: Under close supervision of a physical therapist or physical therapy assistant, perform only delegated, selected, or routine tasks in specific situations. These duties include preparing the patient and the treatment area.

data.title: Other healthcare support jobs
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Massage therapists
data.def: Perform therapeutic massages of soft tissues and joints. May assist in the assessment of range of motion and muscle strength, or propose client therapy plans.

data.title: Miscellaneous healthcare support jobs
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Dental assistants
data.def: Perform limited clinical duties under the direction of a dentist. Clinical duties may include equipment preparation and sterilization, preparing patients for treatment, assisting the dentist during treatment, and providing patients with instructions for oral healthcare procedures. May perform administrative duties such as scheduling appointments, maintaining medical records, billing, and coding information for insurance purposes.

data.title: Medical assistants
data.def: Perform administrative and certain clinical duties under the direction of a physician. Administrative duties may include scheduling appointments, maintaining medical records, billing, and coding information for insurance purposes. Clinical duties may include taking and recording vital signs and medical histories, preparing patients for examination, drawing blood, and administering medications as directed by physician. Excludes “Physician Assistants” (29-1071).

data.title: Medical equipment preparers
data.def: Prepare, sterilize, install, or clean laboratory or healthcare equipment. May perform routine laboratory tasks and operate or inspect equipment.

data.title: Medical transcriptionists
data.def: Transcribe medical reports recorded by physicians and other healthcare practitioners using various electronic devices, covering office visits, emergency room visits, diagnostic imaging studies, operations, chart reviews, and final summaries. Transcribe dictated reports and translate abbreviations into fully understandable form. Edit as necessary and return reports in either printed or electronic form for review and signature, or correction.

data.title: Pharmacy aides
data.def: Record drugs delivered to the pharmacy, store incoming merchandise, and inform the supervisor of stock needs. May operate cash register and accept prescriptions for filling.

data.title: Veterinary assistants and laboratory animal caretakers
data.soc_title: Veterinary Assistants and Laboratory Animal Caretakers
data.def: Feed, water, and examine pets and other nonfarm animals for signs of illness, disease, or injury in laboratories and animal hospitals and clinics. Clean and disinfect cages and work areas, and sterilize laboratory and surgical equipment. May provide routine postoperative care, administer medication orally or topically, or prepare samples for laboratory examination under the supervision of veterinary or laboratory animal technologists or technicians, veterinarians, or scientists. Excludes “Animal Caretakers” (39-2021).

data.title: Phlebotomists
data.def: Draw blood for tests, transfusions, donations, or research. May explain the procedure to patients and assist in the recovery of patients with adverse reactions.

data.title: Healthcare support workers, all other
data.def: All healthcare support workers not listed separately.

data.title: Protective service jobs
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Supervisors of protective service workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: First-line supervisors of law enforcement workers
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Law Enforcement Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: First-line supervisors of correctional officers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of correctional officers and jailers.

data.title: First-line supervisors of police and detectives
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Police and Detectives
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of members of police force.

data.title: First-line supervisors of firefighting and prevention workers
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Firefighting and Prevention Workers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of workers engaged in firefighting and fire prevention and control.

data.title: Miscellaneous first-line supervisors, protective service workers
data.soc_title: Miscellaneous First-Line Supervisors, Protective Service Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: First-line supervisors of security workers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of security workers and security guards.

data.title: First-line supervisors of protective service workers, all other
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Protective Service Workers, All Other
data.def: All protective service supervisors not listed separately above.

data.title: Firefighting and prevention workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Firefighters
data.def: Control and extinguish fires or respond to emergency situations where life, property, or the environment is at risk. Duties may include fire prevention, emergency medical service, hazardous material response, search and rescue, and disaster assistance.

data.title: Fire inspectors
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Fire inspectors and investigators
data.def: Inspect buildings to detect fire hazards and enforce local ordinances and state laws, or investigate and gather facts to determine cause of fires and explosions.

data.title: Forest fire inspectors and prevention specialists
data.soc_title: Forest Fire Inspectors and Prevention Specialists
data.def: Enforce fire regulations, inspect forest for fire hazards, and recommend forest fire prevention or control measures. May report forest fires and weather conditions.

data.title: Law enforcement workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Bailiffs, correctional officers, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Bailiffs
data.def: Maintain order in courts of law.

data.title: Correctional officers and jailers
data.def: Guard inmates in penal or rehabilitative institutions in accordance with established regulations and procedures. May guard prisoners in transit between jail, courtroom, prison, or other point. Includes deputy sheriffs and police who spend the majority of their time guarding prisoners in correctional institutions.

data.title: Detectives and criminal investigators
data.def: Conduct investigations related to suspected violations of federal, state, or local laws to prevent or solve crimes. Excludes “Private Detectives and Investigators” (33-9021).

data.title: Fish and game wardens
data.def: Patrol assigned area to prevent fish and game law violations. Investigate reports of damage to crops or property by wildlife. Compile biological data.

data.title: Parking enforcement workers
data.def: Patrol assigned area, such as public parking lot or city streets to issue tickets to overtime parking violators and illegally parked vehicles.

data.title: Police officers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Police and sheriff's patrol officers
data.def: Maintain order and protect life and property by enforcing local, tribal, state, or federal laws and ordinances. Perform a combination of the following duties: patrol a specific area; direct traffic; issue traffic summonses; investigate accidents; apprehend and arrest suspects, or serve legal processes of courts. Includes police officers working at educational institutions.

data.title: Transit and railroad police
data.def: Protect and police railroad and transit property, employees, or passengers.

data.title: Other protective service workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Animal control workers
data.def: Handle animals for the purpose of investigations of mistreatment, or control of abandoned, dangerous, or unattended animals.

data.title: Private detectives and investigators
data.def: Gather, analyze, compile, and report information regarding individuals or organizations to clients, or detect occurrences of unlawful acts or infractions of rules in private establishment.

data.title: Security guards and gambling surveillance officers
data.soc_title: Security Guards and Gambling Surveillance Officers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Gambling surveillance officers and gambling investigators
data.soc_title: Gambling Surveillance Officers and Gambling Investigators
data.def: Observe gambling operation for irregular activities such as cheating or theft by either employees or patrons. Investigate potential threats to gambling assets such as money, chips, and gambling equipment. Act as oversight and security agent for management and customers.

data.title: Security guards
data.def: Guard, patrol, or monitor premises to prevent theft, violence, or infractions of rules. May operate x-ray and metal detector equipment. Excludes “Police Officers” (33-3050) and “Transportation Security Screeners” (33-9093).

data.title: Miscellaneous protective service workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Crossing guards and flaggers
data.def: Guide or control vehicular or pedestrian traffic at such places as streets, schools, railroad crossings, or construction sites.

data.title: Lifeguards, ski patrol, etc
data.soc_title: Lifeguards, Ski Patrol, and Other Recreational Protective Service Workers
data.def: Monitor recreational areas, such as pools, beaches, or ski slopes, to provide assistance and protection to participants.

data.title: Transportation security screeners
data.def: Conduct screening of passengers, baggage, or cargo to ensure compliance with Transportation Security Administration (TSA) regulations. May operate basic security equipment such as x-ray machines and hand wands at screening checkpoints.

data.title: School bus monitors
data.def: Maintain order among students on a school bus. Duties include helping students safely board and exit and communicating behavioral problems. May perform pretrip and posttrip inspections and prepare for and assist in emergency evacuations.

data.title: Protective service workers, all other
data.def: All protective service workers not listed separately.

data.title: Food preparation and serving related jobs
data.soc_title: Food Preparation and Serving Related Occupations
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Supervisors of food preparation and serving workers
data.soc_title: Supervisors of Food Preparation and Serving Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Chefs and head cooks
data.def: Direct and may participate in the preparation, seasoning, and cooking of salads, soups, fish, meats, vegetables, desserts, or other foods. May plan and price menu items, order supplies, and keep records and accounts.

data.title: First-line supervisors of food preparation and serving workers
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Food Preparation and Serving Workers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of workers engaged in preparing and serving food.

data.title: Cooks and food preparation workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Cooks
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Cooks, fast food
data.def: Prepare and cook food in a fast food restaurant with a limited menu. Duties of these cooks are limited to preparation of a few basic items and normally involve operating large-volume single-purpose cooking equipment.

data.title: Cooks, institution and cafeteria
data.def: Prepare and cook large quantities of food for institutions, such as schools, hospitals, or cafeterias.

data.title: Cooks, private household
data.def: Prepare meals in private homes. Includes personal chefs.

data.title: Cooks, restaurant
data.def: Prepare, season, and cook dishes such as soups, meats, vegetables, or desserts in restaurants. May order supplies, keep records and accounts, price items on menu, or plan menu.

data.title: Cooks, short order
data.def: Prepare and cook to order a variety of foods that require only a short preparation time. May take orders from customers and serve patrons at counters or tables. Excludes “Cooks, Fast Food” (35-2011).

data.title: Cooks, all other
data.def: All cooks not listed separately.

data.title: Food preparation workers
data.def: Perform a variety of food preparation duties other than cooking, such as preparing cold foods and shellfish, slicing meat, and brewing coffee or tea.

data.title: Food and beverage serving workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Bartenders
data.def: Mix and serve drinks to patrons, directly or through waitstaff.

data.title: Fast food and counter workers
data.def: Perform duties such as taking orders and serving food and beverages. Serve customers at counter or from a steam table. May take payment. May prepare food and beverages. Counter attendants who also wait tables are included in “Waiters and Waitresses” (35-3031),

data.title: Waiters and waitresses
data.def: Take orders and serve food and beverages to patrons at tables in dining establishment. Excludes “Fast Food and Counter Workers” (35-3023).

data.title: Food servers, nonrestaurant
data.def: Serve food to individuals outside of a restaurant environment, such as in hotel rooms, hospital rooms, residential care facilities, or cars. Excludes “Fast Food and Counter Workers” (35-3023) and “Door-to-Door Sales Workers, News and Street Vendors, and Related Workers” (41-9091).

data.title: Other food preparation and serving related workers
data.soc_title: Other Food Preparation and Serving Related Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Dining room and cafeteria attendants and bartender helpers
data.soc_title: Dining Room and Cafeteria Attendants and Bartender Helpers
data.def: Facilitate food service. Clean tables; remove dirty dishes; replace soiled table linens; set tables; replenish supply of clean linens, silverware, glassware, and dishes; supply service bar with food; and serve items such as water, condiments, and coffee to patrons.

data.title: Dishwashers
data.def: Clean dishes, kitchen, food preparation equipment, or utensils.

data.title: Hosts and hostesses, restaurant, etc
data.soc_title: Hosts and Hostesses, Restaurant, Lounge, and Coffee Shop
data.def: Welcome patrons, seat them at tables or in lounge, and help ensure quality of facilities and service.

data.title: Food preparation and serving related workers, all other
data.soc_title: Food Preparation and Serving Related Workers, All Other
data.def: All food preparation and serving related workers not listed separately.

data.title: Building and grounds cleaning and maintenance jobs
data.soc_title: Building and Grounds Cleaning and Maintenance Occupations
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Supervisors of building and grounds cleaning and maintenance workers
data.soc_title: Supervisors of Building and Grounds Cleaning and Maintenance Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: First-line supervisors of housekeeping and janitorial workers
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Housekeeping and Janitorial Workers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate work activities of cleaning personnel in hotels, hospitals, offices, and other establishments.

data.title: First-line supervisors of landscaping, lawn service, etc
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Landscaping, Lawn Service, and Groundskeeping Workers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of workers engaged in landscaping or groundskeeping activities.
