Work may involve reviewing contracts to ascertain service, machine, and workforce requirements; answering inquiries from potential customers regarding methods, material, and price ranges; and preparing estimates according to labor, material, and machine costs.

data.title: Building cleaning and pest control workers
data.soc_title: Building Cleaning and Pest Control Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Building cleaning workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Janitors and cleaners, except maids and housekeeping cleaners
data.soc_title: Janitors and Cleaners, Except Maids and Housekeeping Cleaners
data.def: Keep buildings in clean and orderly condition. Perform heavy cleaning duties, such as cleaning floors, shampooing rugs, washing walls and glass, and removing rubbish. Duties may include tending furnace and boiler, performing routine maintenance activities, notifying management of need for repairs, and cleaning snow or debris from sidewalk.

data.title: Maids and housekeeping cleaners
data.def: Perform any combination of light cleaning duties to maintain private households or commercial establishments, such as hotels and hospitals, in a clean and orderly manner. Duties may include making beds, replenishing linens, cleaning rooms and halls, and vacuuming.

data.title: Building cleaning workers, all other
data.def: All building cleaning workers not listed separately.

data.title: Pest control workers
data.def: Apply or release chemical solutions or toxic gases and set traps to kill or remove pests and vermin that infest buildings and surrounding areas.

data.title: Grounds maintenance workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Landscaping and groundskeeping workers
data.def: Landscape or maintain grounds of property using hand or power tools or equipment. Workers typically perform a variety of tasks, which may include any combination of the following: sod laying, mowing, trimming, planting, watering, fertilizing, digging, raking, sprinkler installation, and installation of mortarless segmental concrete masonry wall units. Excludes “Farmworkers and Laborers, Crop, Nursery, and Greenhouse” (45-2092).

data.title: Pesticide handlers, sprayers, etc
data.soc_title: Pesticide Handlers, Sprayers, and Applicators, Vegetation
data.def: Mix or apply pesticides, herbicides, fungicides, or insecticides through sprays, dusts, vapors, soil incorporation, or chemical application on trees, shrubs, lawns, or crops. Usually requires specific training and state or federal certification. Crop dusters are included in “Commercial Pilots” (53-2012).

data.title: Tree trimmers and pruners
data.def: Using sophisticated climbing and rigging techniques, cut away dead or excess branches from trees or shrubs to maintain right-of-way for roads, sidewalks, or utilities, or to improve appearance, health, and value of tree. Prune or treat trees or shrubs using handsaws, hand pruners, clippers, and power pruners. Works off the ground in the tree canopy and may use truck-mounted lifts. Excludes workers who primarily perform duties of “Landscaping and Groundskeeping Workers” (37-3011) and “Pesticide Handlers, Sprayers, and Applicators, Vegetation” (37-3012).

data.title: Grounds maintenance workers, all other
data.def: All grounds maintenance workers not listed separately.

data.title: Personal care and service jobs
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Supervisors of personal care and service workers
data.soc_title: Supervisors of Personal Care and Service Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: First-line supervisors of entertainment and recreation workers
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Entertainment and Recreation Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: First-line supervisors of gambling services workers
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Gambling Services Workers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of workers in assigned gambling areas. May circulate among tables, observe operations, and ensure that stations and games are covered for each shift. May verify and pay off jackpots. May reset slot machines after payoffs and make repairs or adjustments to slot machines or recommend removal of slot machines for repair. May plan and organize activities and services for guests in hotels/casinos.

data.title: First-line supervisors of entertainment and recreation workers, except gambling services
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Entertainment and Recreation Workers, Except Gambling Services
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of entertainment and recreation related workers.

data.title: First-line supervisors of personal service workers
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Personal Service Workers
data.def: Supervise and coordinate activities of personal service workers.

data.title: Animal care and service workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Animal trainers
data.def: Train animals for riding, harness, security, performance, or obedience, or for assisting persons with disabilities. Accustom animals to human voice and contact, and condition animals to respond to commands. Train animals according to prescribed standards for show or competition. May train animals to carry pack loads or work as part of pack team.

data.title: Animal caretakers
data.def: Feed, water, groom, bathe, exercise, or otherwise provide care to promote and maintain the well-being of pets and other animals that are not raised for consumption, such as dogs, cats, race horses, ornamental fish or birds, zoo animals, and mice. Work in settings such as kennels, animal shelters, zoos, circuses, and aquariums. May keep records of feedings, treatments, and animals received or discharged. May clean, disinfect, and repair cages, pens, or fish tanks. Excludes “Veterinary Assistants and Laboratory Animal Caretakers” (31-9096) and “Farmworkers, Farm, Ranch, and Aquacultural Animals” (45-2093).

data.title: Entertainment attendants and related workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Gambling services workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Gambling dealers
data.def: Operate table games. Stand or sit behind table and operate games of chance by dispensing the appropriate number of cards or blocks to players, or operating other gambling equipment. Distribute winnings or collect players’ money or chips. May compare the house’s hand against players’ hands.

data.title: Gambling and sports book writers and runners
data.soc_title: Gambling and Sports Book Writers and Runners
data.def: Post information enabling patrons to wager on various races and sporting events. Assist in the operation of games such as keno and bingo. May operate random number-generating equipment and announce the numbers for patrons. Receive, verify, and record patrons’ wagers. Scan and process winning tickets presented by patrons and pay out winnings for those wagers.

data.title: Gambling service workers, all other
data.def: All gambling service workers not listed separately.

data.title: Motion picture projectionists
data.def: Set up and operate motion picture projection and related sound reproduction equipment.

data.title: Ushers, lobby attendants, etc
data.soc_title: Ushers, Lobby Attendants, and Ticket Takers
data.def: Assist patrons at entertainment events by performing duties, such as collecting admission tickets and passes from patrons, assisting in finding seats, searching for lost articles, and helping patrons locate such facilities as restrooms and telephones.

data.title: Miscellaneous entertainment attendants and related workers
data.soc_title: Miscellaneous Entertainment Attendants and Related Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Amusement and recreation attendants
data.def: Perform a variety of attending duties at amusement or recreation facility. May schedule use of recreation facilities, maintain and provide equipment to participants of sporting events or recreational pursuits, or operate amusement concessions and rides.

data.title: Costume attendants
data.def: Select, fit, and take care of costumes for cast members, and aid entertainers. May assist with multiple costume changes during performances.

data.title: Locker room, coatroom, etc
data.soc_title: Locker Room, Coatroom, and Dressing Room Attendants
data.def: Provide personal items to patrons or customers in locker rooms, dressing rooms, or coatrooms.

data.title: Entertainment attendants and related workers, all other
data.soc_title: Entertainment Attendants and Related Workers, All Other
data.def: All entertainment attendants and related workers not listed separately.

data.title: Funeral service workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Embalmers and crematory operators
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Embalmers
data.def: Prepare bodies for interment in conformity with legal requirements.

data.title: Crematory operators
data.def: Operate crematory equipment to reduce human or animal remains to bone fragments in accordance with state and local regulations. Duties may include preparing the body for cremation and performing general maintenance on crematory equipment. May use traditional flame-based cremation, calcination, or alkaline hydrolysis.

data.title: Funeral attendants
data.def: Perform a variety of tasks during funeral, such as placing casket in parlor or chapel prior to service, arranging floral offerings or lights around casket, directing or escorting mourners, closing casket, and issuing and storing funeral equipment.

data.title: Morticians, undertakers, etc
data.def: Perform various tasks to arrange and direct individual funeral services, such as coordinating transportation of body to mortuary, interviewing family or other authorized person to arrange details, selecting pallbearers, aiding with the selection of officials for religious rites, and providing transportation for mourners. Excludes “Funeral Home Managers” (11-9171).

data.title: Personal appearance workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Barbers, hairdressers, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Barbers
data.def: Provide barbering services, such as cutting, trimming, shampooing, and styling hair; trimming beards; or giving shaves.

data.title: Hairdressers, hairstylists, etc
data.def: Provide beauty services, such as cutting, coloring, and styling hair, and massaging and treating scalp. May shampoo hair, apply makeup, dress wigs, remove hair, and provide nail and skincare services. Excludes “Makeup Artists, Theatrical and Performance” (39-5091), “Manicurists and Pedicurists” (39-5092), and “Skincare Specialists” (39-5094).

data.title: Miscellaneous personal appearance workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Makeup artists, theatrical and performance
data.def: Apply makeup to performers to reflect period, setting, and situation of their role.

data.title: Manicurists and pedicurists
data.def: Clean and shape customers’ fingernails and toenails. May polish or decorate nails.

data.title: Shampooers
data.def: Shampoo and rinse customers’ hair.

data.title: Skincare specialists
data.def: Provide skincare treatments to face and body to enhance an individual’s appearance. Includes electrologists and laser hair removal specialists.

data.title: Baggage porters, bellhops, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Baggage porters and bellhops
data.def: Handle baggage for travelers at transportation terminals or for guests at hotels or similar establishments.

data.title: Concierges
data.def: Assist patrons at hotel, apartment, or office building with personal services. May take messages; arrange or give advice on transportation, business services, or entertainment; or monitor guest requests for housekeeping and maintenance.

data.title: Tour and travel guides
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Tour and travel guides
data.def: No job definition found.

data.title: Other personal care and service workers
data.soc_title: Other Personal Care and Service Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Childcare workers
data.def: Attend to children at schools, businesses, private households, and childcare institutions. Perform a variety of tasks, such as dressing, feeding, bathing, and overseeing play. Excludes “Preschool Teachers, Except Special Education” (25-2011) and “Teaching Assistants, Preschool, Elementary, Middle, and Secondary School, Except Special Education” (25-9042).

data.title: Recreation and fitness workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Exercise trainers and group fitness instructors
data.soc_title: Exercise Trainers and Group Fitness Instructors
data.def: Instruct or coach groups or individuals in exercise activities for the primary purpose of personal fitness. Demonstrate techniques and form, observe participants, and explain to them corrective measures necessary to improve their skills. Develop and implement individualized approaches to exercise. Excludes “Educational Instruction and Library Occupations” (25-0000), “Coaches and Scouts” (27-2022), and “Athletic Trainers” (29-9091).

data.title: Recreation workers
data.def: Conduct recreation activities with groups in public, private, or volunteer agencies or recreation facilities. Organize and promote activities, such as arts and crafts, sports, games, music, dramatics, social recreation, camping, and hobbies, taking into account the needs and interests of individual members.

data.title: Residential advisors
data.def: Coordinate activities in resident facilities in secondary school and college dormitories, group homes, or similar establishments. Order supplies and determine need for maintenance, repairs, and furnishings. May maintain household records and assign rooms. May assist residents with problem solving or refer them to counseling resources.

data.title: Personal care and service workers, all other
data.soc_title: Personal Care and Service Workers, All Other
data.def: All personal care and service workers not listed separately.

data.title: Sales and related jobs
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Supervisors of sales workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: First-line supervisors of retail sales workers
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Retail Sales Workers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of retail sales workers in an establishment or department. Duties may include management functions, such as purchasing, budgeting, accounting, and personnel work, in addition to supervisory duties.

data.title: First-line supervisors of non-retail sales workers
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Non-Retail Sales Workers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of sales workers other than retail sales workers. May perform duties such as budgeting, accounting, and personnel work, in addition to supervisory duties.

data.title: Retail sales workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Cashiers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Cashiers
data.def: Receive and disburse money in establishments other than financial institutions. May use electronic scanners, cash registers, or related equipment. May process credit or debit card transactions and validate checks. Excludes “Gambling Change Persons and Booth Cashiers” (41-2012).

data.title: Gambling change persons and booth cashiers
data.soc_title: Gambling Change Persons and Booth Cashiers
data.def: Exchange coins, tokens, and chips for patrons’ money. May issue payoffs and obtain customer’s signature on receipt. May operate a booth in the slot machine area and furnish change persons with money bank at the start of the shift, or count and audit money in drawers. Excludes “Cashiers” (41-2011).

data.title: Counter and rental clerks and parts salespersons
data.soc_title: Counter and Rental Clerks and Parts Salespersons
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Counter and rental clerks
data.def: Receive orders, generally in person, for repairs, rentals, and services. May describe available options, compute cost, and accept payment. Excludes “Fast Food and Counter Workers” (35-3023), “Hotel, Motel, and Resort Desk Clerks” (43-4081), “Order Clerks” (43-4151), and “Reservation and Transportation Ticket Agents and Travel Clerks” (43-4181).

data.title: Parts salespersons
data.def: Sell spare and replacement parts and equipment in repair shop or parts store.

data.title: Retail salespersons
data.def: Sell merchandise, such as furniture, motor vehicles, appliances, or apparel to consumers. Excludes “Cashiers” (41-2011).

data.title: Sales representatives, services
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Advertising sales agents
data.def: Sell or solicit advertising space, time, or media in publications, signage, TV, radio, or Internet establishments or public spaces.

data.title: Insurance sales agents
data.def: Sell life, property, casualty, health, automotive, or other types of insurance. May refer clients to independent brokers, work as an independent broker, or be employed by an insurance company.

data.title: Securities, commodities, etc
data.soc_title: Securities, Commodities, and Financial Services Sales Agents
data.def: Buy and sell securities or commodities in investment and trading firms, or provide financial services to businesses and individuals. May advise customers about stocks, bonds, mutual funds, commodities, and market conditions.

data.title: Travel agents
data.def: Plan and sell transportation and accommodations for customers. Determine destination, modes of transportation, travel dates, costs, and accommodations required. May also describe, plan, and arrange itineraries and sell tour packages. May assist in resolving clients’ travel problems.

data.title: Sales representatives of services, except advertising, etc
data.soc_title: Sales Representatives of Services, Except Advertising, Insurance, Financial Services, and Travel
data.def: Sell services to individuals or businesses. May describe options or resolve client problems. Excludes “Advertising Sales Agents” (41-3011), “Insurance Sales Agents” (41-3021), “Securities, Commodities, and Financial Services Sales Agents” (41-3031), “Travel Agents” (41-3041), “Sales Representatives, Wholesale and Manufacturing” (41-4010), and “Telemarketers” (41-9041).

data.title: Sales representatives, wholesale and manufacturing
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Sales representatives, wholesale and manufacturing, etc
data.soc_title: Sales Representatives, Wholesale and Manufacturing, Technical and Scientific Products
data.def: Sell goods for wholesalers or manufacturers where technical or scientific knowledge is required in such areas as biology, engineering, chemistry, and electronics, normally obtained from at least 2 years of postsecondary education. Excludes “Sales Engineers” (41-9031).

data.title: Sales representatives, wholesale and manufacturing, etc
data.soc_title: Sales Representatives, Wholesale and Manufacturing, Except Technical and Scientific Products
data.def: Sell goods for wholesalers or manufacturers to businesses or groups of individuals. Work requires substantial knowledge of items sold.

data.title: Other sales and related workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Models, demonstrators, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Demonstrators and product promoters
data.def: Demonstrate merchandise and answer questions for the purpose of creating public interest in buying the product. May sell demonstrated merchandise.

data.title: Models
data.def: Model garments or other apparel and accessories for prospective buyers at fashion shows, private showings, or retail establishments. May pose for photos to be used in magazines or advertisements. May pose as subject for paintings, sculptures, and other types of artistic expression.

data.title: Real estate brokers and sales agents
data.soc_title: Real Estate Brokers and Sales Agents
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Real estate brokers
data.def: Operate real estate office, or work for commercial real estate firm, overseeing real estate transactions. Other duties usually include selling real estate or renting properties and arranging loans.

data.title: Real estate sales agents
data.def: Rent, buy, or sell property for clients. Perform duties such as study property listings, interview prospective clients, accompany clients to property site, discuss conditions of sale, and draw up real estate contracts. Includes agents who represent buyer.

data.title: Sales engineers
data.def: Sell business goods or services, the selling of which requires a technical background equivalent to a baccalaureate degree in engineering. Excludes “Engineers” (17-2011 through 17-2199) whose primary function is not marketing or sales.

data.title: Telemarketers
data.def: Solicit donations or orders for goods or services over the telephone.

data.title: Miscellaneous sales and related workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Door-to-door sales workers, news and street vendors, etc
data.soc_title: Door-to-Door Sales Workers, News and Street Vendors, and Related Workers
data.def: Sell goods or services door-to-door or on the street.

data.title: Sales and related workers, all other
data.soc_title: Sales and Related Workers, All Other
data.def: All sales and related workers not listed separately.

data.title: Office and administrative support jobs
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Supervisors of office and administrative support workers
data.soc_title: Supervisors of Office and Administrative Support Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: First-line supervisors of office and administrative support workers
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Office and Administrative Support Workers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate the activities of clerical and administrative support workers.

data.title: Communications equipment operators
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Switchboard operators, including answering service
data.def: Operate telephone business systems equipment or switchboards to relay incoming, outgoing, and interoffice calls. May supply information to callers and record messages.

data.title: Telephone operators
data.def: Provide information by accessing alphabetical, geographical, or other directories. Assist customers with special billing requests, such as charges to a third party and credits or refunds for incorrectly dialed numbers or bad connections. May handle emergency calls and assist children or people with physical disabilities to make telephone calls.

data.title: Communications equipment operators, all other
data.def: All communications equipment operators not listed separately.

data.title: Financial clerks
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Bill and account collectors
data.def: Locate and notify customers of delinquent accounts by mail, telephone, or personal visit to solicit payment. Duties include receiving payment and posting amount to customer’s account, preparing statements to credit department if customer fails to respond, initiating repossession proceedings or service disconnection, and keeping records of collection and status of accounts.

data.title: Billing and posting clerks
data.def: Compile, compute, and record billing, accounting, statistical, and other numerical data for billing purposes. Prepare billing invoices for services rendered or for delivery or shipment of goods. Excludes “Medical Records Specialists” (29-2072).

data.title: Bookkeeping, accounting, etc
data.def: Compute, classify, and record numerical data to keep financial records complete. Perform any combination of routine calculating, posting, and verifying duties to obtain primary financial data for use in maintaining accounting records. May also check the accuracy of figures, calculations, and postings pertaining to business transactions recorded by other workers. Excludes “Payroll and Timekeeping Clerks” (43-3051).

data.title: Gambling cage workers
data.def: In a gambling establishment, conduct financial transactions for patrons. Accept patron’s credit application and verify credit references to provide check-cashing authorization or to establish house credit accounts. May reconcile daily summaries of transactions to balance books. May sell gambling chips, tokens, or tickets to patrons, or to other workers for resale to patrons. May convert gambling chips, tokens, or tickets to currency upon patron’s request. May use a cash register or computer to record transaction.

data.title: Payroll and timekeeping clerks
data.def: Compile and record employee time and payroll data. May compute employees’ time worked, production, and commission. May compute and post wages and deductions, or prepare paychecks. Excludes “Bookkeeping, Accounting, and Auditing Clerks” (43-3031).

data.title: Procurement clerks
data.def: Compile information and records to draw up purchase orders for procurement of materials and services. Excludes “Wholesale and Retail Buyers, Except Farm Products” (13-1022).

data.title: Tellers
data.def: Receive and pay out money. Keep records of money and negotiable instruments involved in a financial institution’s various transactions.

data.title: Financial clerks, all other
data.def: All financial clerks not listed separately.

data.title: Information and record clerks
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Brokerage clerks
data.def: Perform duties related to the purchase, sale, or holding of securities. Duties include writing orders for stock purchases or sales, computing transfer taxes, verifying stock transactions, accepting and delivering securities, tracking stock price fluctuations, computing equity, distributing dividends, and keeping records of daily transactions and holdings.

data.title: Correspondence clerks
data.def: Compose letters or electronic correspondence in reply to requests for merchandise, damage claims, credit and other information, delinquent accounts, incorrect billings, or unsatisfactory services. Duties may include gathering data to formulate reply and preparing correspondence.

data.title: Court, municipal, etc
data.def: Perform clerical duties for courts of law, municipalities, or governmental licensing agencies and bureaus. May prepare docket of cases to be called; secure information for judges and court; prepare draft agendas or bylaws for town or city council; answer official correspondence; keep fiscal records and accounts; issue licenses or permits; and record data, administer tests, or collect fees. Clerks of Court are classified in “Managers, All Other” (11-9199).

data.title: Credit authorizers, checkers, etc
data.def: Authorize credit charges against customers’ accounts. Investigate history and credit standing of individuals or business establishments applying for credit. May interview applicants to obtain personal and financial data, determine credit worthiness, process applications, and notify customers of acceptance or rejection of credit.

data.title: Customer service representatives
data.def: Interact with customers to provide basic or scripted information in response to routine inquiries about products and services. May handle and resolve general complaints. Excludes individuals whose duties are primarily installation, sales, repair, and technical support.

data.title: Eligibility interviewers, government programs
data.def: Determine eligibility of persons applying to receive assistance from government programs and agency resources, such as welfare, unemployment benefits, social security, and public housing.

data.title: File clerks
data.def: File correspondence, cards, invoices, receipts, and other records in alphabetical or numerical order or according to the filing system used. Locate and remove material from file when requested.

data.title: Hotel, motel, etc
data.soc_title: Hotel, Motel, and Resort Desk Clerks
data.def: Accommodate hotel, motel, and resort patrons by registering and assigning rooms to guests, issuing room keys or cards, transmitting and receiving messages, keeping records of occupied rooms and guests’ accounts, making and confirming reservations, and presenting statements to and collecting payments from departing guests.

data.title: Interviewers, except eligibility and loan
data.def: Interview persons by telephone, mail, in person, or by other means for the purpose of completing forms, applications, or questionnaires. Ask specific questions, record answers, and assist persons with completing form. May sort, classify, and file forms.

data.title: Library assistants, clerical
data.def: Compile records, and sort, shelve, issue, and receive library materials such as books, electronic media, pictures, cards, slides and microfilm. Locate library materials for loan and replace material in shelving area, stacks, or files according to identification number and title. Register patrons to permit them to borrow books, periodicals, and other library materials. Excludes “Library Technicians” (25-4031).

data.title: Loan interviewers and clerks
data.def: Interview loan applicants to elicit information; investigate applicants’ backgrounds and verify references; prepare loan request papers; and forward findings, reports, and documents to appraisal department. Review loan papers to ensure completeness, and complete transactions between loan establishment, borrowers, and sellers upon approval of loan.

data.title: New accounts clerks
data.def: Interview persons desiring to open accounts in financial institutions. Explain account services available to prospective customers and assist them in preparing applications.

data.title: Order clerks
data.def: Receive and process incoming orders for materials, merchandise, classified ads, or services such as repairs, installations, or rental of facilities. Generally receives orders via mail, phone, fax, or other electronic means. Duties include informing customers of receipt, prices, shipping dates, and delays; preparing contracts; and handling complaints. Excludes “Dispatchers, Except Police, Fire, and Ambulance” (43-5032) who both dispatch and take orders for services.

data.title: Human resources assistants, except payroll and timekeeping
data.soc_title: Human Resources Assistants, Except Payroll and Timekeeping
data.def: Compile and keep personnel records. Record data for each employee, such as address, weekly earnings, absences, amount of sales or production, supervisory reports, and date of and reason for termination. May prepare reports for employment records, file employment records, or search employee files and furnish information to authorized persons.

data.title: Receptionists and information clerks
data.def: Answer inquiries and provide information to the general public, customers, visitors, and other interested parties regarding activities conducted at establishment and location of departments, offices, and employees within the organization. Excludes “Switchboard Operators, Including Answering Service” (43-2011).

data.title: Reservation and transportation ticket agents and travel clerks
data.soc_title: Reservation and Transportation Ticket Agents and Travel Clerks
data.def: Make and confirm reservations for transportation or lodging, or sell transportation tickets. May check baggage and direct passengers to designated concourse, pier, or track; deliver tickets and contact individuals and groups to inform them of package tours; or provide tourists with travel or transportation information. Excludes "Cashiers” (41-2011), "Travel Agents” (41-3041), and "Hotel, Motel, and Resort Desk Clerks” (43-4081) who sell tickets for local transportation.

data.title: Information and record clerks, all other
data.soc_title: Information and Record Clerks, All Other
data.def: All information and record clerks not listed separately.

data.title: Material recording, scheduling, etc
data.soc_title: Material Recording, Scheduling, Dispatching, and Distributing Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Cargo and freight agents
data.def: Expedite and route movement of incoming and outgoing cargo and freight shipments in airline, train, and trucking terminals and shipping docks. Take orders from customers and arrange pickup of freight and cargo for delivery to loading platform. Prepare and examine bills of lading to determine shipping charges and tariffs.

data.title: Couriers and messengers
data.def: Pick up and deliver messages, documents, packages, and other items between offices or departments within an establishment or directly to other business concerns, traveling by foot, bicycle, motorcycle, automobile, or public conveyance. Excludes “Light Truck Drivers” (53-3033).

data.title: Dispatchers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Public safety telecommunicators
data.def: Operate telephone, radio, or other communication systems to receive and communicate requests for emergency assistance at 9-1-1 public safety answering points and emergency operations centers. Take information from the public and other sources regarding crimes, threats, disturbances, acts of terrorism, fires, medical emergencies, and other public safety matters. May coordinate and provide information to law enforcement and emergency response personnel. May access sensitive databases and other information sources as needed. May provide additional instructions to callers based on knowledge of and certification in law enforcement, fire, or emergency medical procedures.

data.title: Dispatchers, except police, etc
data.soc_title: Dispatchers, Except Police, Fire, and Ambulance
data.def: Schedule and dispatch workers, work crews, equipment, or service vehicles for conveyance of materials, freight, or passengers, or for normal installation, service, or emergency repairs rendered outside the place of business. Duties may include using radio, telephone, or computer to transmit assignments and compiling statistics and reports on work progress.

data.title: Meter readers, utilities
data.def: Read meter and record consumption of electricity, gas, water, or steam.

data.title: Postal service workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Postal service clerks
data.def: Perform any combination of tasks in a United States Postal Service (USPS) post office, such as receive letters and parcels; sell postage and revenue stamps, postal cards, and stamped envelopes; fill out and sell money orders; place mail in pigeon holes of mail rack or in bags; and examine mail for correct postage. Includes postal service clerks employed by USPS contractors.

data.title: Postal service mail carriers
data.def: Sort and deliver mail for the United States Postal Service (USPS). Deliver mail on established route by vehicle or on foot. Includes postal service mail carriers employed by USPS contractors.

data.title: Postal service mail sorters, processors, etc
data.soc_title: Postal Service Mail Sorters, Processors, and Processing Machine Operators
data.def: Prepare incoming and outgoing mail for distribution for the United States Postal Service (USPS). Examine, sort, and route mail. Load, operate, and occasionally adjust and repair mail processing, sorting, and canceling machinery. Keep records of shipments, pouches, and sacks, and perform other duties related to mail handling within the postal service. Includes postal service mail sorters and processors employed by USPS contractors. Excludes “Postal Service Clerks” (43-5051) and “Postal Service Mail Carriers” (43-5052).

data.title: Production, planning, etc
data.def: Coordinate and expedite the flow of work and materials within or between departments of an establishment according to production schedule. Duties include reviewing and distributing production, work, and shipment schedules; conferring with department supervisors to determine progress of work and completion dates; and compiling reports on progress of work, inventory levels, costs, and production problems. Excludes “Project Management Specialists” (13-1082) and “Weighers, Measurers, Checkers, and Samplers, Recordkeeping” (43-5111).

data.title: Shipping, receiving, etc
data.def: Verify and maintain records on incoming and outgoing shipments involving inventory. Duties include verifying and recording incoming merchandise or material and arranging for the transportation of products. May prepare items for shipment. Excludes “Weighers, Measurers, Checkers, and Samplers, Recordkeeping” (43-5111), “Mail Clerks and Mail Machine Operators, except Postal Service” (43-9051), and “Stockers and Order Fillers” (53-7065).

data.title: Weighers, measurers, etc
data.soc_title: Weighers, Measurers, Checkers, and Samplers, Recordkeeping
data.def: Weigh, measure, and check materials, supplies, and equipment for the purpose of keeping relevant records. Duties are primarily clerical by nature. Includes workers who collect and keep record of samples of products or materials. Excludes “Inspectors, Testers, Sorters, Samplers, and Weighers” (51-9061).

data.title: Secretaries and administrative assistants
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Executive secretaries and executive administrative assistants
data.soc_title: Executive Secretaries and Executive Administrative Assistants
data.def: Provide high-level administrative support by conducting research, preparing statistical reports, and handling information requests, as well as performing routine administrative functions such as preparing correspondence, receiving visitors, arranging conference calls, and scheduling meetings. May also train and supervise lower-level clerical staff. Excludes “Secretaries” (43-6012 through 43-6014).

data.title: Legal secretaries and administrative assistants
data.def: Perform secretarial duties using legal terminology, procedures, and documents. Prepare legal papers and correspondence, such as summonses, complaints, motions, and subpoenas. May also assist with legal research.

data.title: Medical secretaries and administrative assistants
data.def: Perform secretarial duties using specific knowledge of medical terminology and hospital, clinic, or laboratory procedures. Duties may include scheduling appointments, billing patients, and compiling and recording medical charts, reports, and correspondence.

data.title: Secretaries and administrative assistants, except legal, etc
data.soc_title: Secretaries and Administrative Assistants, Except Legal, Medical, and Executive
data.def: Perform routine administrative functions such as drafting correspondence, scheduling appointments, organizing and maintaining paper and electronic files, or providing information to callers. Excludes legal, medical, and executive secretaries (43-6011 through 43-6013).

data.title: Other office and administrative support workers
data.soc_title: Other Office and Administrative Support Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Data entry and information processing workers
data.soc_title: Data Entry and Information Processing Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Data entry keyers
data.def: Operate data entry device, such as keyboard or photo composing perforator. Duties may include verifying data and preparing materials for printing. Excludes “Word Processors and Typists” (43-9022).

data.title: Word processors and typists
data.def: Use word processor, computer, or typewriter to type letters, reports, forms, or other material from rough draft, corrected copy, or voice recording. May perform other clerical duties as assigned. Excludes “Court Reporters and Simultaneous Captioners” (27-3092), “Medical Transcriptionists” (31-9094), “Secretaries and Administrative Assistants” (43-6010), and “Data Entry Keyers” (43-9021).

data.title: Desktop publishers
data.def: Format typescript and graphic elements using computer software to produce publication-ready material.

data.title: Insurance claims and policy processing clerks
data.soc_title: Insurance Claims and Policy Processing Clerks
data.def: Process new insurance policies, modifications to existing policies, and claims forms. Obtain information from policyholders to verify the accuracy and completeness of information on claims forms, applications and related documents, and company records. Update existing policies and company records to reflect changes requested by policyholders and insurance company representatives. Excludes “Claims Adjusters, Examiners, and Investigators” (13-1031).

data.title: Mail clerks and mail machine operators, except postal service
data.soc_title: Mail Clerks and Mail Machine Operators, Except Postal Service
data.def: Prepare incoming and outgoing mail for distribution. Time-stamp, open, read, sort, and route incoming mail; and address, seal, stamp, fold, stuff, and affix postage to outgoing mail or packages. Duties may also include keeping necessary records and completed forms.

data.title: Office clerks, general
data.def: Perform duties too varied and diverse to be classified in any specific office clerical occupation, requiring knowledge of office systems and procedures. Clerical duties may be assigned in accordance with the office procedures of individual establishments and may include a combination of answering telephones, bookkeeping, typing or word processing, office machine operation, and filing.

data.title: Office machine operators, except computer
data.def: Operate one or more of a variety of office machines, such as photocopying, photographic, and duplicating machines, or other office machines. Excludes “Billing and Posting Clerks” (43-3021) and “Mail Clerks and Mail Machine Operators, Except Postal Service” (43-9051).

data.title: Proofreaders and copy markers
data.def: Read transcript or proof type setup to detect and mark for correction any grammatical, typographical, or compositional errors. Excludes workers whose primary duty is editing copy. Includes proofreaders of braille.

data.title: Statistical assistants
data.def: Compile and compute data according to statistical formulas for use in statistical studies. May perform actuarial computations and compile charts and graphs for use by actuaries. Includes actuarial clerks.

data.title: Office and administrative support workers, all other
data.soc_title: Office and Administrative Support Workers, All Other
data.def: All office and administrative support workers not listed separately.

data.title: Farming, fishing, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Supervisors of farming, fishing, etc
data.soc_title: Supervisors of Farming, Fishing, and Forestry Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: First-line supervisors of farming, fishing, etc
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Farming, Fishing, and Forestry Workers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate the activities of agricultural, forestry, aquacultural, and related workers. Excludes “First-Line Supervisors of Landscaping, Lawn Service, and Groundskeeping Workers” (37-1012).

data.title: Agricultural workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Agricultural inspectors
data.def: Inspect agricultural commodities, processing equipment, and facilities, and fish and logging operations, to ensure compliance with regulations and laws governing health, quality, and safety.

data.title: Animal breeders
data.def: Select and breed animals according to their genealogy, characteristics, and offspring. May require knowledge of artificial insemination techniques and equipment use. May involve keeping records on heats, birth intervals, or pedigree. Excludes “Animal Scientists” (19-1011) whose primary function is research and “Animal Caretakers” (39-2021) who may occasionally breed animals as part of their other caretaking duties.

data.title: Graders and sorters, agricultural products
data.def: Grade, sort, or classify unprocessed food and other agricultural products by size, weight, color, or condition. Excludes “Agricultural Inspectors” (45-2011).

data.title: Miscellaneous agricultural workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Agricultural equipment operators
data.def: Drive and control equipment to support agricultural activities such as tilling soil; planting, cultivating, and harvesting crops; feeding and herding livestock; or removing animal waste. May perform tasks such as crop baling or hay bucking. May operate stationary equipment to perform post-harvest tasks such as husking, shelling, threshing, and ginning.

data.title: Farmworkers and laborers, crop, etc
data.soc_title: Farmworkers and Laborers, Crop, Nursery, and Greenhouse
data.def: Manually plant, cultivate, and harvest vegetables, fruits, nuts, horticultural specialties, and field crops. Use hand tools, such as shovels, trowels, hoes, tampers, pruning hooks, shears, and knives. Duties may include tilling soil and applying fertilizers; transplanting, weeding, thinning, or pruning crops; applying pesticides; or cleaning, grading, sorting, packing, and loading harvested products. May construct trellises, repair fences and farm buildings, or participate in irrigation activities. Excludes “Pesticide Handlers, Sprayers, and Applicators, Vegetation” (37-3012), “Graders and Sorters, Agricultural Products” (45-2041), and “Forest, Conservation, and Logging Workers” (45-4011 through 45-4029).

data.title: Farmworkers, farm, etc
data.soc_title: Farmworkers, Farm, Ranch, and Aquacultural Animals
data.def: Attend to live farm, ranch, open range or aquacultural animals that may include cattle, sheep, swine, goats, horses and other equines, poultry, rabbits, finfish, shellfish, and bees. Attend to animals produced for animal products, such as meat, fur, skins, feathers, eggs, milk, and honey. Duties may include feeding, watering, herding, grazing, milking, castrating, branding, de-beaking, weighing, catching, and loading animals. May maintain records on animals; examine animals to detect diseases and injuries; assist in birth deliveries; and administer medications, vaccinations, or insecticides as appropriate. May clean and maintain animal housing areas. Includes workers who shear wool from sheep and collect eggs in hatcheries.

data.title: Agricultural workers, all other
data.def: All agricultural workers not listed separately.

data.title: Fishing and hunting workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Fishing and hunting workers
data.def: Hunt, trap, catch, or gather wild animals or aquatic animals and plants. May use nets, traps, or other equipment. May haul catch onto ship or other vessel. Aquacultural laborers who work on fish farms are included in “Farmworkers, Farm, Ranch, and Aquacultural Animals” (45-2093).

data.title: Forest, conservation, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Forest and conservation workers
data.def: Under supervision, perform manual labor necessary to develop, maintain, or protect areas such as forests, forested areas, woodlands, wetlands, and rangelands through such activities as raising and transporting seedlings; combating insects, pests, and diseases harmful to plant life; and building structures to control water, erosion, and leaching of soil. Includes forester aides, seedling pullers, tree planters, and gatherers of nontimber forestry products such as pine straw.

data.title: Logging workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Fallers
data.def: Use axes or chainsaws to fell trees using knowledge of tree characteristics and cutting techniques to control direction of fall and minimize tree damage.

data.title: Logging equipment operators
data.def: Drive logging tractor or wheeled vehicle equipped with one or more accessories, such as bulldozer blade, frontal shear, grapple, logging arch, cable winches, hoisting rack, or crane boom, to fell tree; to skid, load, unload, or stack logs; or to pull stumps or clear brush. Includes operating stand-alone logging machines, such as log chippers. Logging truck drivers are included in “Heavy and Tractor-Trailer Truck Drivers” (53-3032).

data.title: Log graders and scalers
data.def: Grade logs or estimate the marketable content or value of logs or pulpwood in sorting yards, millpond, log deck, or similar locations. Inspect logs for defects or measure logs to determine volume. Excludes “Buyers and Purchasing Agents, Farm Products” (13-1021).

data.title: Logging workers, all other
data.def: All logging workers not listed separately.

data.title: Construction and extraction jobs
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Supervisors of construction and extraction workers
data.soc_title: Supervisors of Construction and Extraction Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: First-line supervisors of construction trades and extraction workers
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Construction Trades and Extraction Workers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate activities of construction or extraction workers.

data.title: Construction trades workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Boilermakers
data.def: Construct, assemble, maintain, and repair stationary steam boilers and boiler house auxiliaries. Align structures or plate sections to assemble boiler frame tanks or vats, following blueprints. Work involves use of hand and power tools, plumb bobs, levels, wedges, dogs, or turnbuckles. Assist in testing assembled vessels. Direct cleaning of boilers and boiler furnaces. Inspect and repair boiler fittings, such as safety valves, regulators, automatic-control mechanisms, water columns, and auxiliary machines.

data.title: Brickmasons, blockmasons, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Brickmasons and blockmasons
data.def: Lay and bind building materials, such as brick, structural tile, concrete block, cinder block, glass block, and terra-cotta block, with mortar and other substances, to construct or repair walls, partitions, arches, sewers, and other structures. Installers of mortarless segmental concrete masonry wall units are classified in “Landscaping and Groundskeeping Workers” (37-3011). Excludes “Stonemasons” (47-2022).

data.title: Stonemasons
data.def: Build stone structures, such as piers, walls, and abutments. Lay walks, curbstones, or special types of masonry for vats, tanks, and floors.

data.title: Carpenters
data.def: Construct, erect, install, or repair structures and fixtures made of wood and comparable materials, such as concrete forms; building frameworks, including partitions, joists, studding, and rafters; and wood stairways, window and door frames, and hardwood floors. May also install cabinets, siding, drywall, and batt or roll insulation. Includes brattice builders who build doors or brattices (ventilation walls or partitions) in underground passageways.

data.title: Carpet, floor, etc
data.soc_title: Carpet, Floor, and Tile Installers and Finishers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Carpet installers
data.def: Lay and install carpet from rolls or blocks on floors. Install padding and trim flooring materials. Excludes “Floor Layers, Except Carpet, Wood, and Hard Tiles” (47-2042).

data.title: Floor layers, except carpet, etc
data.soc_title: Floor Layers, Except Carpet, Wood, and Hard Tiles
data.def: Apply blocks, strips, or sheets of shock-absorbing, sound-deadening, or decorative coverings to floors.

data.title: Floor sanders and finishers
data.def: Scrape and sand wooden floors to smooth surfaces using floor scraper and floor sanding machine, and apply coats of finish.

data.title: Tile and stone setters
data.def: Apply hard tile, stone, and comparable materials to walls, floors, ceilings, countertops, and roof decks.

data.title: Cement masons, concrete finishers, etc
data.soc_title: Cement Masons, Concrete Finishers, and Terrazzo Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Cement masons and concrete finishers
data.def: Smooth and finish surfaces of poured concrete, such as floors, walks, sidewalks, roads, or curbs using a variety of hand and power tools. Align forms for sidewalks, curbs, or gutters; patch voids; and use saws to cut expansion joints. Installers of mortarless segmental concrete masonry wall units are classified in “Landscaping and Groundskeeping Workers” (37-3011).

data.title: Terrazzo workers and finishers
data.def: Apply a mixture of cement, sand, pigment, or marble chips to floors, stairways, and cabinet fixtures to fashion durable and decorative surfaces.

data.title: Construction laborers
data.def: Perform tasks involving physical labor at construction sites. May operate hand and power tools of all types: air hammers, earth tampers, cement mixers, small mechanical hoists, surveying and measuring equipment, and a variety of other equipment and instruments. May clean and prepare sites, dig trenches, set braces to support the sides of excavations, erect scaffolding, and clean up rubble, debris, and other waste materials. May assist other craft workers. Construction laborers who primarily assist a particular craft worker are classified under “Helpers, Construction Trades” (47-3010). Excludes “Hazardous Materials Removal Workers” (47-4041).

data.title: Construction equipment operators
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Paving, surfacing, etc
data.soc_title: Paving, Surfacing, and Tamping Equipment Operators
data.def: Operate equipment used for applying concrete, asphalt, or other materials to road beds, parking lots, or airport runways and taxiways or for tamping gravel, dirt, or other materials. Includes concrete and asphalt paving machine operators, form tampers, tamping machine operators, and stone spreader operators.

data.title: Pile driver operators
data.def: Operate pile drivers mounted on skids, barges, crawler treads, or locomotive cranes to drive pilings for retaining walls, bulkheads, and foundations of structures such as buildings, bridges, and piers.

data.title: Operating engineers and other construction equipment operators
data.soc_title: Operating Engineers and Other Construction Equipment Operators
data.def: Operate one or several types of power construction equipment, such as motor graders, bulldozers, scrapers, compressors, pumps, derricks, shovels, tractors, or front-end loaders to excavate, move, and grade earth, erect structures, or pour concrete or other hard surface pavement. May repair and maintain equipment in addition to other duties. Excludes “Extraction Workers” (47-5000) and “Crane and Tower Operators” (53-7021).

data.title: Drywall installers, ceiling tile installers, etc
data.soc_title: Drywall Installers, Ceiling Tile Installers, and Tapers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Drywall and ceiling tile installers
data.def: Apply plasterboard or other wallboard to ceilings or interior walls of buildings. Apply or mount acoustical tiles or blocks, strips, or sheets of shock-absorbing materials to ceilings and walls of buildings to reduce or reflect sound. Materials may be of decorative quality. Includes lathers who fasten wooden, metal, or rockboard lath to walls, ceilings, or partitions of buildings to provide support base for plaster, fireproofing, or acoustical material. Excludes “Carpenters” (47-2031), “Carpet Installers” (47-2041), and “Tile and Stone Setters” (47-2044).

data.title: Tapers
data.def: Seal joints between plasterboard or other wallboard to prepare wall surface for painting or papering.

data.title: Electricians
data.def: Install, maintain, and repair electrical wiring, equipment, and fixtures. Ensure that work is in accordance with relevant codes. May install or service street lights, intercom systems, or electrical control systems. Excludes “Security and Fire Alarm Systems Installers” (49-2098).

data.title: Glaziers
data.def: Install glass in windows, skylights, store fronts, and display cases, or on surfaces, such as building fronts, interior walls, ceilings, and tabletops.

data.title: Insulation workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Insulation workers, floor, etc
data.soc_title: Insulation Workers, Floor, Ceiling, and Wall
data.def: Line and cover structures with insulating materials. May work with batt, roll, or blown insulation materials.

data.title: Insulation workers, mechanical
data.def: Apply insulating materials to pipes or ductwork, or other mechanical systems in order to help control and maintain temperature.

data.title: Painters and paperhangers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Painters, construction and maintenance
data.def: Paint walls, equipment, buildings, bridges, and other structural surfaces, using brushes, rollers, and spray guns. May remove old paint to prepare surface prior to painting. May mix colors or oils to obtain desired color or consistency. Excludes “Paperhangers” (47-2142).

data.title: Paperhangers
data.def: Cover interior walls or ceilings of rooms with decorative wallpaper or fabric, or attach advertising posters on surfaces such as walls and billboards. May remove old materials or prepare surfaces to be papered.

data.title: Pipelayers, plumbers, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Pipelayers
data.def: Lay pipe for storm or sanitation sewers, drains, and water mains. Perform any combination of the following tasks: grade trenches or culverts, position pipe, or seal joints. Excludes “Welders, Cutters, Solderers, and Brazers” (51-4121).

data.title: Plumbers, pipefitters, etc
data.def: Assemble, install, alter, and repair pipelines or pipe systems that carry water, steam, air, or other liquids or gases. May install heating and cooling equipment and mechanical control systems. Includes sprinkler fitters.

data.title: Plasterers and stucco masons
data.def: Apply interior or exterior plaster, cement, stucco, or similar materials. May also set ornamental plaster.

data.title: Reinforcing iron and rebar workers
data.def: Position and secure steel bars or mesh in concrete forms in order to reinforce concrete. Use a variety of fasteners, rod-bending machines, blowtorches, and hand tools. Includes rod busters.

data.title: Roofers
data.def: Cover roofs of structures with shingles, slate, asphalt, aluminum, wood, or related materials. May spray roofs, sidings, and walls with material to bind, seal, insulate, or soundproof sections of structures.

data.title: Sheet metal workers
data.def: Fabricate, assemble, install, and repair sheet metal products and equipment, such as ducts, control boxes, drainpipes, and furnace casings. Work may involve any of the following: setting up and operating fabricating machines to cut, bend, and straighten sheet metal; shaping metal over anvils, blocks, or forms using hammer; operating soldering and welding equipment to join sheet metal parts; or inspecting, assembling, and smoothing seams and joints of burred surfaces. Includes sheet metal duct installers who install prefabricated sheet metal ducts used for heating, air conditioning, or other purposes.

data.title: Structural iron and steel workers
data.def: Raise, place, and unite iron or steel girders, columns, and other structural members to form completed structures or structural frameworks. May erect metal storage tanks and assemble prefabricated metal buildings. Excludes “Reinforcing Iron and Rebar Workers” (47-2171).

data.title: Solar photovoltaic installers
data.def: Assemble, install, or maintain solar photovoltaic (PV) systems on roofs or other structures in compliance with site assessment and schematics. May include measuring, cutting, assembling, and bolting structural framing and solar modules. May perform minor electrical work such as current checks. Excludes solar PV electricians who are included in “Electricians” (47-2111) and solar thermal installers who are included in “Plumbers, Pipefitters, and Steamfitters” (47-2152).

data.title: Helpers, construction trades
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Helpers--brickmasons, blockmasons, etc
data.soc_title: Helpers--Brickmasons, Blockmasons, Stonemasons, and Tile and Marble Setters
data.def: Help brickmasons, blockmasons, stonemasons, or tile and marble setters by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist brickmasons, blockmasons, and stonemasons or tile and marble setters are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

data.title: Helpers--carpenters
data.def: Help carpenters by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist carpenters are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

data.title: Helpers--electricians
data.def: Help electricians by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist electricians are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

data.title: Helpers--painters, paperhangers, etc
data.soc_title: Helpers--Painters, Paperhangers, Plasterers, and Stucco Masons
data.def: Help painters, paperhangers, plasterers, or stucco masons by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist painters, paperhangers, plasterers, or stucco masons are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

data.title: Helpers--pipelayers, plumbers, etc
data.def: Help plumbers, pipefitters, steamfitters, or pipelayers by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist plumbers, pipefitters, steamfitters, or pipelayers are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

data.title: Helpers--roofers
data.def: Help roofers by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include using, supplying, or holding materials or tools, and cleaning work area and equipment. Construction laborers who do not primarily assist roofers are classified under “Construction Laborers” (47-2061). Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

data.title: Helpers, construction trades, etc
data.def: All construction trades helpers not listed separately.

data.title: Other construction and related workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Construction and building inspectors
data.def: Inspect structures using engineering skills to determine structural soundness and compliance with specifications, building codes, and other regulations. Inspections may be general in nature or may be limited to a specific area, such as electrical systems or plumbing.

data.title: Elevator and escalator installers and repairers
data.soc_title: Elevator and Escalator Installers and Repairers
data.def: Assemble, install, repair, or maintain electric or hydraulic freight or passenger elevators, escalators, or dumbwaiters.

data.title: Fence erectors
data.def: Erect and repair fences and fence gates, using hand and power tools.

data.title: Hazardous materials removal workers
data.def: Identify, remove, pack, transport, or dispose of hazardous materials, including asbestos, lead-based paint, waste oil, fuel, transmission fluid, radioactive materials, or contaminated soil. Specialized training and certification in hazardous materials handling or a confined entry permit are generally required. May operate earth-moving equipment or trucks.

data.title: Highway maintenance workers
data.def: Maintain highways, municipal and rural roads, airport runways, and rights-of-way. Duties include patching broken or eroded pavement and repairing guard rails, highway markers, and snow fences. May also mow or clear brush from along road, or plow snow from roadway. Excludes “Tree Trimmers and Pruners” (37-3013).

data.title: Rail-track laying and maintenance equipment operators
data.soc_title: Rail-Track Laying and Maintenance Equipment Operators
data.def: Lay, repair, and maintain track for standard or narrow-gauge railroad equipment used in regular railroad service or in plant yards, quarries, sand and gravel pits, and mines. Includes ballast cleaning machine operators and railroad bed tamping machine operators.

data.title: Septic tank servicers and sewer pipe cleaners
data.soc_title: Septic Tank Servicers and Sewer Pipe Cleaners
data.def: Clean and repair septic tanks, sewer lines, or drains. May patch walls and partitions of tank, replace damaged drain tile, or repair breaks in underground piping.

data.title: Miscellaneous construction and related workers
data.def: No job definition found.

data.title: Extraction workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Derrick, rotary drill, etc
data.soc_title: Derrick, Rotary Drill, and Service Unit Operators, Oil and Gas
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Derrick operators, oil and gas
data.def: Rig derrick equipment and operate pumps to circulate mud or fluid through drill hole.

data.title: Rotary drill operators, oil and gas
data.soc_title: Rotary Drill Operators, Oil and Gas
data.def: Set up or operate a variety of drills to remove underground oil and gas, or remove core samples for testing during oil and gas exploration. Excludes “Earth Drillers, Except Oil and Gas” (47-5023).

data.title: Service unit operators, oil and gas
data.soc_title: Service Unit Operators, Oil and Gas
data.def: Operate equipment to increase oil flow from producing wells or to remove stuck pipe, casing, tools, or other obstructions from drilling wells. Includes fishing-tool technicians.

data.title: Surface mining machine operators and earth drillers
data.soc_title: Surface Mining Machine Operators and Earth Drillers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Excavating and loading machine and dragline operators, surface mining
data.soc_title: Excavating and Loading Machine and Dragline Operators, Surface Mining
data.def: Operate or tend machinery at surface mining site, equipped with scoops, shovels, or buckets to excavate and load loose materials.

data.title: Earth drillers, except oil and gas
data.soc_title: Earth Drillers, Except Oil and Gas
data.def: Operate a variety of drills such as rotary, churn, and pneumatic to tap subsurface water and salt deposits, to remove core samples during mineral exploration or soil testing, and to facilitate the use of explosives in mining or construction. Includes horizontal and earth boring machine operators.

data.title: Explosives workers, ordnance handling experts, etc
data.soc_title: Explosives Workers, Ordnance Handling Experts, and Blasters
data.def: Place and detonate explosives to demolish structures or to loosen, remove, or displace earth, rock, or other materials. May perform specialized handling, storage, and accounting procedures.

data.title: Underground mining machine operators
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Continuous mining machine operators
data.def: Operate self-propelled mining machines that rip coal, metal and nonmetal ores, rock, stone, or sand from the mine face and load it onto conveyors, shuttle cars, or trucks in a continuous operation.

data.title: Roof bolters, mining
data.def: Operate machinery to install roof support bolts in underground mine.

data.title: Loading and moving machine operators, underground mining
data.soc_title: Loading and Moving Machine Operators, Underground Mining
data.def: Operate underground loading or moving machine to load or move coal, ore, or rock using shuttle or mine car or conveyors. Equipment may include power shovels, hoisting engines equipped with cable-drawn scraper or scoop, or machines equipped with gathering arms and conveyor.

data.title: Underground mining machine operators, all other
data.soc_title: Underground Mining Machine Operators, All Other
data.def: All underground mining machine operators not listed separately.

data.title: Rock splitters, quarry
data.def: Separate blocks of rough dimension stone from quarry mass using jackhammers, wedges, or chop saws.

data.title: Roustabouts, oil and gas
data.def: Assemble or repair oil field equipment using hand and power tools. Perform other tasks as needed.

data.title: Helpers--extraction workers
data.def: Help extraction craft workers, such as earth drillers, blasters and explosives workers, derrick operators, and mining machine operators, by performing duties requiring less skill. Duties include supplying equipment or cleaning work area. Apprentice workers are classified with the appropriate skilled construction trade occupation (47-2011 through 47-2231).

data.title: Extraction workers, all other
data.def: All extraction workers not listed separately.

data.title: Installation, maintenance, etc
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Supervisors of installation, maintenance, etc
data.soc_title: Supervisors of Installation, Maintenance, and Repair Workers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: First-line supervisors of mechanics, installers, etc
data.soc_title: First-Line Supervisors of Mechanics, Installers, and Repairers
data.def: Directly supervise and coordinate the activities of mechanics, installers, and repairers. May also advise customers on recommended services. Excludes team or work leaders.

data.title: Electrical and electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc
data.soc_title: Electrical and Electronic Equipment Mechanics, Installers, and Repairers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Computer, automated teller, etc
data.soc_title: Computer, Automated Teller, and Office Machine Repairers
data.def: Repair, maintain, or install computers, word processing systems, automated teller machines, and electronic office machines, such as duplicating and fax machines.

data.title: Radio and telecommunications equipment installers and repairers
data.soc_title: Radio and Telecommunications Equipment Installers and Repairers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Radio, cellular, etc
data.soc_title: Radio, Cellular, and Tower Equipment Installers and Repairers
data.def: Repair, install, or maintain mobile or stationary radio transmitting, broadcasting, and receiving equipment, and two-way radio communications systems used in cellular telecommunications, mobile broadband, ship-to-shore, aircraft-to-ground communications, and radio equipment in service and emergency vehicles. May test and analyze network coverage.

data.title: Telecommunications equipment installers and repairers, except line installers
data.soc_title: Telecommunications Equipment Installers and Repairers, Except Line Installers
data.def: Install, set up, rearrange, or remove switching, distribution, routing, and dialing equipment used in central offices or headends. Service or repair telephone, cable television, Internet, and other communications equipment on customers’ property. May install communications equipment or communications wiring in buildings. Excludes “Telecommunications Line Installers and Repairers” (49-9052).

data.title: Miscellaneous electrical and electronic equipment mechanics, installers, etc
data.soc_title: Miscellaneous Electrical and Electronic Equipment Mechanics, Installers, and Repairers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Avionics technicians
data.def: Install, inspect, test, adjust, or repair avionics equipment, such as radar, radio, navigation, and missile control systems in aircraft or space vehicles.

data.title: Electric motor, power tool, etc
data.soc_title: Electric Motor, Power Tool, and Related Repairers
data.def: Repair, maintain, or install electric motors, wiring, or switches.

data.title: Electrical and electronics installers and repairers, transportation equipment
data.soc_title: Electrical and Electronics Installers and Repairers, Transportation Equipment
data.def: Install, adjust, or maintain mobile electronics communication equipment, including sound, sonar, security, navigation, and surveillance systems on trains, watercraft, or other mobile equipment. Excludes “Avionics Technicians” (49-2091) and “Electronic Equipment Installers and Repairers, Motor Vehicles” (49-2096).

data.title: Electrical and electronics repairers, commercial and industrial equipment
data.soc_title: Electrical and Electronics Repairers, Commercial and Industrial Equipment
data.def: Repair, test, adjust, or install electronic equipment, such as industrial controls, transmitters, and antennas. Excludes “Avionics Technicians” (49-2091), “Electrical and Electronics Installers and Repairers, Transportation Equipment” (49-2093), and “Electronic Equipment Installers and Repairers, Motor Vehicles” (49-2096).

data.title: Electrical and electronics repairers, powerhouse, etc
data.soc_title: Electrical and Electronics Repairers, Powerhouse, Substation, and Relay
data.def: Inspect, test, repair, or maintain electrical equipment in generating stations, substations, and in-service relays.

data.title: Electronic equipment installers and repairers, motor vehicles
data.soc_title: Electronic Equipment Installers and Repairers, Motor Vehicles
data.def: Install, diagnose, or repair communications, sound, security, or navigation equipment in motor vehicles.

data.title: Audiovisual equipment installers and repairers
data.def: Install, repair, or adjust audio or television receivers, stereo systems, camcorders, video systems, or other electronic entertainment equipment in homes or other venues. May perform routine maintenance. Excludes “Audio and Video Technicians” (27-4011).

data.title: Security and fire alarm systems installers
data.soc_title: Security and Fire Alarm Systems Installers
data.def: Install, program, maintain, and repair security and fire alarm wiring and equipment. Ensure that work is in accordance with relevant codes. Excludes “Electricians” (47-2111) who do a broad range of electrical wiring.

data.title: Vehicle and mobile equipment mechanics, installers, etc
data.soc_title: Vehicle and Mobile Equipment Mechanics, Installers, and Repairers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Aircraft mechanics and service technicians
data.def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul aircraft engines and assemblies, such as hydraulic and pneumatic systems. Excludes “Avionics Technicians” (49-2091).

data.title: Automotive technicians and repairers
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Automotive body and related repairers
data.def: Repair and refinish automotive vehicle bodies and straighten vehicle frames. Excludes “Automotive Glass Installers and Repairers” (49-3022) and “Coating, Painting, and Spraying Machine Setters, Operators, and Tenders” (51-9124).

data.title: Automotive glass installers and repairers
data.def: Replace or repair broken windshields and window glass in motor vehicles.

data.title: Automotive service technicians and mechanics
data.def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul automotive vehicles. Excludes “Automotive Body and Related Repairers” (49-3021), “Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists” (49-3031), and “Electronic Equipment Installers and Repairers, Motor Vehicles” (49-2096).

data.title: Bus and truck mechanics and diesel engine specialists
data.soc_title: Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists
data.def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul buses and trucks, or maintain and repair any type of diesel engines. Includes mechanics working primarily with automobile or marine diesel engines.

data.title: Heavy vehicle and mobile equipment service technicians and mechanics
data.soc_title: Heavy Vehicle and Mobile Equipment Service Technicians and Mechanics
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Farm equipment mechanics and service technicians
data.soc_title: Farm Equipment Mechanics and Service Technicians
data.def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul farm machinery and vehicles, such as tractors, harvesters, dairy equipment, and irrigation systems. Excludes “Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists” (49-3031).

data.title: Mobile heavy equipment mechanics, except engines
data.soc_title: Mobile Heavy Equipment Mechanics, Except Engines
data.def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul mobile mechanical, hydraulic, and pneumatic equipment, such as cranes, bulldozers, graders, and conveyors, used in construction, logging, and mining. Excludes “Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists” (49-3031) and “Rail Car Repairers” (49-3043).

data.title: Rail car repairers
data.def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul railroad rolling stock, mine cars, or mass transit rail cars. Excludes “Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists” (49-3031).

data.title: Small engine mechanics
data.def: No definition found for this Summary Category.

data.title: Motorboat mechanics and service technicians
data.def: Repair and adjust electrical and mechanical equipment of inboard or inboard-outboard boat engines. Excludes “Bus and Truck Mechanics and Diesel Engine Specialists” (49-3031).

data.title: Motorcycle mechanics
data.def: Diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul motorcycles, scooters, mopeds, dirt bikes, or similar motorized vehicles.

data.title: Outdoor power equipment and other small engine mechanics
data.soc_title: Outdoor Power Equipment and Other Small Engine Mechanics
